<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Buffalo-Niagara Falls No. 1 in union membership, stats show  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Finally, Buffalo can say ''We're No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   It may not be the hockey or football title residents long for,
but federal statistics show the Buffalo-Niagara Falls metro area is
first in the nation when it comes to union membership.
</P>
<P>
   Bolstered by a heavy union presence in the public sector, a
factor throughout New York state, plus union strength in the
industrial job base, the 27.3 percent rate of membership is nearly
double the national average of 14 percent, Bureau of National
Affairs statistics show.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think (labor's influence) has helped protect the quality of
life,'' Buffalo Common Council member Mary Martino told The Buffalo
News. The former vice president of a nurses union, Martino said
union members in her district usually have a better health and
retirement safety net than nonunion members.
</P>
<P>
   However, union dues do not buy job security, as 340 mostly
unionized workers at Occidental Chemical Co. found out last week
when the company announced it is closing operations in Niagara
Falls and Grand Island.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is the pro-union reputation a selling point when it comes to
luring companies to replace lost jobs, development officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's no secret, if you ask the site selection guys, the fact
participation is high is an eliminator for us in searches,'' said
Thomas Kucharski, president of the Buffalo Niagara Enterprise, a
business coalition that hopes to attract 50,000 new jobs in five
years.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bottom line is, most companies state a strong preference
to remaining nonunion when they site a new facility,'' agreed
Dennis Donovan, a site selection consultant with the Wadley-Donovan
group in Morristown, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Nonunion companies oppose sharing authority, Donovan said, and
avoid areas where unions are strong. The exceptions are high-tech
and service industries, which usually are not unionized.
</P>
<P>
   Rochester, which last month passed Buffalo in jobs, has 15
percent union membership, No. 38 on the list of 100 metropolitan
areas. Farther down the list are Austin, Texas, and Raleigh-Durham,
N.C., where job growth races ahead of the national average.
</P>
<P>
   While it may not help attract jobs, labor leaders said union
strength contributes to better wages and conditions for people in
existing jobs. The average weekly paycheck for a union worker was
$650 last year in Buffalo, 25 percent more than nonunion wages,
federal data shows.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Buffalo and Niagara Falls-area unions formed the
AFL-CIO Development Group to market the region to employers, hoping
to dispel the negative perception of area unions.
</P>
<P>
   ''Organized labor is cooperative with management. The idea is to
bring good jobs here,'' said coalition spokesman Kevin Donovan.
</P>
<P>
   Allied Signal, Quebecor Printing, American Axle &AMP; Manufacturing
and other companies have said their unions worked with management
to strengthen the company. At American Axle, for example, an
innovative contract with the UAW allowed the company to open a
100-job factory last year in Cheektowaga that performs work
formerly done by out-of-state suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   It was partly a change in federal record-keeping that put the
Buffalo-Niagara Falls area atop the list of union strongholds
during the 1990s, the Buffalo News said. The change combined Flint,
Mich., and some other union towns with nearby cities, taking them
out of the running.
</P>
<P>
   Slow job growth also increased Buffalo's union density. While
other cities gained jobs, mostly nonunion ones, the Niagara
region's job total barely budged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
