<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Catholic bishops speak of 'false success' of welfare reform  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The state's Roman Catholic bishops are
calling on Gov. George Pataki and the state Legislature to
determine conclusively what has become of former welfare recipients
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Both common sense and compassion dictate that the state find out
more about the lives of some 800,000 people who were on welfare in
1995 and are not any more, the state Catholic Conference said.
</P>
<P>
   Welfare rolls in New York have dropped almost by half from the
1.6 million people receiving public assistance when Pataki became
governor in 1995. His administration said the research done so far
indicates the bulk of those people are gainfully employed and
leading productive lives.
</P>
<P>
   In their most recent pronouncement on welfare, delivered to a
state Senate hearing in New York City late last week, the bishops
said there is more call for emergency food, clothing and shelter
provided by Catholic Charities in the state.
</P>
<P>
   That suggests to Catholic leaders that welfare reform has
resulted in ''false success,'' Kathleen Ayers Lanzillotta told the
Senate hearing on behalf of the bishops. She is administrator for
substance abuse services of Catholic Charities run by the diocese
of Rockville Centre on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is easy and seductive to claim that they have left welfare
for work, but the state has not completed evaluations that were
mandated under federal and state welfare reform laws,'' Lanzillotta
said.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear to the Catholic Conference whether the failure to
definitively track former welfare recipients is intentional or not,
conference spokesman Rick Hinshaw said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unfortunately, you get into the political sound bite,''
Hinshaw said. ''It sounds good to say you've reduced the rolls by
this much. It's almost a question of why look for trouble from a
political standpoint. 'This (numbers drop) is good news.' Maybe
there is a hesitancy to dig deeper and to find that the news is not
as good as you think.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Catholic Conference official, David Hamilton said
Catholic Charity workers in Albany and on Long Island have
interviewed more than 500 people recently coming into their food
pantries and found that most feel they are worse off than they were
six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The state should be tracking those people to determine how
effective welfare reform has really been, Hamilton said.
</P>
<P>
   ''All we seem to be seeing are closed cases in state data,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pataki administration argued, however, that it is doing just
what the bishops are calling for.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, the State University of New York's Rockefeller
Institute of Government reported that 83 percent of 8,983 families
who had left welfare in the first quarter of 1997 were not on
welfare one year later. The study also found 75 percent of the
former welfare recipients had been employed at some point since
leaving the rolls.
</P>
<P>
   The state Office of Temporary and Disability Assistance (OTDA)
said it has two other studies currently underway. One is examining
people who have been receiving public assistance since December
1996 since those people will be the first to face an automatic
cut-off of benefits after five years. The other is tracking people
who left public assistance in 1999 to see what transitional benefit
programs work and what do not, according to OTDA spokesman Jack
Madden.
</P>
<P>
   Planned studies will look at would-be welfare recipients who are
diverted into other assistance programs and at the role drug and
alcohol abuse has on the welfare system, Madden said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-30-00 0010 </TRAILER>
