<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Won't Pressure Taiwan Over Talks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- The United States will not pressure Taiwan
to accept China's conditions for talks between the two rivals, the
top U.S. representative in Taiwan said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The comments by Raymond Burghardt, director of the American
Institute in Taiwan, were apparently aimed at calming Taiwanese who
fear that Washington might team up with Beijing and try to force
Taiwan to the bargaining table.
</P>
<P>
   New Taiwanese President Chen Shui-bian has offered to meet with
Chinese leaders. But Beijing has insisted that before talks begin,
Chen must agree that Taiwan is an inseparable part of ''one
China.''
</P>
<P>
   Chen has said he would discuss the issue during a summit, but he
has said he would not agree to any preconditions for the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Burghardt repeated Washington's assurance that it
would not pressure Taipei to accept Beijing's precondition. He also
said that Taiwan and China should solve their differences on their
own.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will support any arrangement that is voluntarily agreed to
by both sides,'' Burghardt, the de facto U.S. ambassador to Taiwan,
said at a conference of scholars.
</P>
<P>
   Like most nations, the United States does not have formal
diplomatic ties with Taiwan, which split from China amid civil war
51 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   China considers Taiwan to be a breakaway province and uses its
political and economic clout to discourage nations from forming
official ties with it.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Monday, China's state-run media said Chinese President
Jiang Zemin thanked President Clinton in a telephone call for his
help last week in pushing through permanent low-tariff trading
rights for China.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton agreed with Jiang that granting permanent normal trade
relations to China ''will further strengthen the foundation of
U.S.-China relations,'' the official Xinhua News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
   (bf)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
