<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Health care workers, veterans rally against budget cuts  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CHRISTOFFERSEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKY HILL, Conn. (AP) -- On a day set aside to remember fallen
soldiers, a group of health care workers rallied to preserve
medical treatment for today's aging veterans.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 health care workers, veterans and family members
on Monday protested potential budget cuts at the state veterans
hospital in Rocky Hill. Speakers said veterans deserve better
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ''They took care of us,'' said Helen Bergeron, whose husband,
Eugene, is a World War II veteran who lives at the facility. ''Now
we should take care of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The New England Health Care Employees Union District 1199, which
represents about 250 health care employees at the Rocky Hill
facility, said the state Department of Veterans Affairs wants to
eliminate the hospital's acute care license. The change to only
chronic care would mean the loss of physicians and nurses and
eliminate onsite services such as radiology, lab testing and
electrocardiography, union officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The union, which organized the rally, also said the department
projects savings of $395,000 and the elimination of about 27
positions. Several speakers said previous budget cuts have already
hurt services and created poor conditions at the facility,
including inadequate air conditioning and heating, and fewer staff
to supervise veterans with Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   ''The conditions here are deplorable,'' said Edward Kalinowski,
first selectman in Portland whose father, a World War II veteran,
was cared for at the facility until his death last week.
</P>
<P>
   But Veterans Affairs Commissioner Eugene Migliaro charged that
the rally is aimed primarily at preserving bloated overtime
accounts. He said it is inappropriate and disrespectful to scare
veterans and their families on Memorial Day.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no substance to anything that the union is saying,''
Migliaro told the Journal-Inquirer of Manchester on Sunday. ''They
are exploiting these people and on Memorial Day. That's shameful.''
</P>
<P>
   The union said many of the employees are relatives of veterans
and feel strongly about the care they receive.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner said the licensing change was proposed largely
to recognize that many typical acute-care services never have been
provided at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Migliaro did note that, as recommended by a consultant's report,
he eliminated two radiologist positions and may contract out for
some services. But he insisted that hospital operations would not
change much, and the facility's 170 patients would not see any
changes in care.
</P>
<P>
   The state Legislature this month approved a $28.2 million
2000-01 operating budget for the department. And while it
represents a $1 million increase over the current fiscal year, it
falls $322,000 below the level originally projected as necessary to
maintain services.
</P>
<P>
   Migliaro said most of the money can be offset by reductions in
overtime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
