<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fire marshals to push for repeal of legalization  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) --A bill that sailed through the Legislature
could legalize sparklers in time for the Fourth of July, but state
fire marshals want the governor to veto the measure.
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut Fire Marshals Association said that if Gov. John
G. Rowland doesn't act, they will in the next session of the
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the governor doesn't veto it, then I believe it will be a
prime concern for discussion in the next General Assembly,'' said
David Roth, president of the group.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Rowland said the governor plans to sign the
bill, perhaps as early as this week.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, approved with little opposition during the
legislative session, allows people 16 and older to buy and sell
sparklers -- nonexplosive fireworks which give off a shower of
colorful sparks.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut was one of 10 states to ban sparklers, which burn at
1,800 degrees Fahrenheit.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the ban include Prevent Blindness Connecticut, a
nonprofit organization based in Middletown; the Connecticut
Association of Optometrists; the Connecticut Society of Eye
Physicians; and the Connecticut Firefighters Association.
</P>
<P>
   They say sparklers are a fire hazard and danger to children's
health. According to federal government statistics, sparklers are
the second biggest cause of eye injuries that require trips to
hospital emergency rooms.
</P>
<P>
   One pediatric group estimates that sparklers cause up to 7
percent of the nation's estimated 10,000 fireworks-related injuries
a year. Most of the injuries are caused by explosive fireworks,
which would not be legalized under the state bill.
</P>
<P>
   The sparkler proposal was first brought to the legislature's
Public Safety Committee in January. The U.S. Fireworks Safety
Commission, a group formed by makers of nonexplosive fireworks,
hired a Hartford-based lobbyist to push the measure.
</P>
<P>
   No one testified against the bill at a March 7 hearing,
lawmakers said, and the bill was unanimously approved by the Public
Safety Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was not a momentous bill in the scheme of things,'' said
Sen. Alvin Penn, a Bridgeport Democrat who is co-chairman of the
committee. ''We looked at the safety issues. We did not receive any
evidence to show they were any more harmful than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Another committee member, Rep. Ronald San Angelo, R-Naugatuck,
said the bill passed quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think most legislators as kids had sparklers in their lives,
so they thought it was relatively harmless,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Roth, who is East Hartford's fire marshal, said the state fire
marshals group fought the bill with letters to lawmakers and calls
to the governor's office.
</P>
<P>
   Gary S. Keith, of the nonprofit National Fire Protection
Association in Quincy, Mass., wrote to Rowland recommending he kill
the measure.
</P>
<P>
   ''All of us in the fire safety community have spent many years
trying to teach children that fire is not a toy,'' Keith wrote in
the letter, dated May 11. ''The message will be seriously affected
by the contradiction of letting young children use sparklers and
similar devices.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman in the state Department of Public Safety said the
Division of Fire, Emergency and Building Services has received
calls from the public about the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've had calls from people saying they're not happy with
it,'' she said. ''But since the bill hasn't yet been signed, we've
told them to call the governor's office.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-30-00 0103 </TRAILER>
