<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 01:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Politics turns small-town parades into big-time events  </HEADLINE>
By BETH J. HARPAZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Three local Memorial Day parades with the
traditional pageantry of American flags, marching bands and
uniformed veterans turned into high-powered political events
featuring New York's Senate candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Rick Lazio, of Long Island, who was expected to be
nominated by the state Republican Party today in Buffalo to replace
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani as the Republican candidate, marched Monday
with the mayor at a parade in Douglaston, Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, at a parade in Babylon, Lazio was so
enthusiastic about stopping to shake hands that he fell behind the
line of marchers and tripped as he sprinted to catch up. Lazio fell
on his face, cut his top lip and needed eight stitches at Long
Island Jewish Medical Center in New Hyde Park.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was so happy to be back home that I kissed the ground,''
Lazio joked later.
</P>
<P>
   Babylon is in his home district in Suffolk County, and he
recalled having marched in the same parade as a child.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton marched Monday in a parade in her adopted
hometown with the Girl Scouts of Chappaqua, holding the
white-gloved hands of two little girls dressed in Brownie and Daisy
uniforms. Spectators lining the parade route applauded as they
spotted their most famous resident taking part in a treasured local
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hi, Hillary!'' called Grace Bucolo, who works at the local
Grand Union. ''She's gorgeous, absolutely gorgeous. And she's been
in our store a couple of times.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I shook Hillary Clinton's hand! I'm never washing this hand
again,'' announced Julia Deutsch, an 8-year-old Girl Scout.
</P>
<P>
   Chappaqua's only fire trucks were pulled out of the parade to
respond to an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we just got the fire safety badge for getting out of
the way,'' said Clinton, who is the honorary chairwoman for the
Girl Scouts of America, as she led several girls to the side to let
the red trucks pass, sirens blaring.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those who turned out for the parades sported red, white
and blue accessories -- headbands, hats, earrings and scarves.
</P>
<P>
   ''Great sweater!'' Clinton called out to Kerri Moore, who was
wearing a hand-knit sweater bearing a flag design.
</P>
<P>
   Moore politely smiled and waved back but admitted privately that
she is a registered Conservative.
</P>
<P>
   ''Her telling me she liked my sweater won't sway my vote,''
Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   David Metz, clutching a copy of Peggy Noonan's book ''The Case
Against Hillary Clinton'' was less reserved.
</P>
<P>
   ''Go back to Illinois!'' he shouted as Clinton walked by.
</P>
<P>
   Politics was also on the minds of spectators in Queens, who
shouted ''Go get her, Rick!'' and ''Give her hell!'' as Lazio
passed by. He and the mayor zigzagged from the march to the curb to
work the crowd and engage in a little mutual admiration.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're very enthusiastic about his candidacy,'' said Giuliani,
who dropped out of the race for treatment of prostate cancer.
''He's gotten off to an absolutely tremendous start, and if I could
judge by the reception here in northern Queens, he's going to be a
very, very strong candidate. ... I'm going to do everything I can
to help him get elected.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he felt about the mayor's support, Lazio said:
''Believe me, it's very welcome. He's a tremendously popular
figure. He's done a great job for the city of New York, and he
believes in the same things I'm talking about -- work and
responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, son of an Army veteran father and a Navy veteran mother,
added: ''Memorial Day is a very special day for me, having both
parents who served our country in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also reminisced about parades from her childhood in a
suburb of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ''I marched in parades with the Girl Scouts probably every
Memorial Day ever since I was in first or second grade, all through
high school, in a town that was about the size of Chappaqua,'' she
said. ''I loved being here and meeting a lot of my neighbors and
seeing a lot of the kids. It was a great day, and it was pretty
nostalgic.''
</P>
<P>
   When the parade was over, Clinton bought coffee for her staff at
a local deli, Lange's, where she was invited to go behind the
counter to shake hands. As she stood with a group of workers in
white aprons, she joked, ''If the Senate race doesn't work out,
I'll get a job here.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Lazio campaign: http://www.lazio.com
</P>
<P>
   Clinton campaign: http://www.hillary2000.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
