<DOCNO> APW20000530.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 01:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N. Ireland Regains Some Authority  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Northern Ireland regained a
measure of self-rule today, giving the province's Protestant and
Catholic leaders another chance to achieve a lasting peace.
</P>
<P>
   Britain handed back powers at midnight (7:00 p.m. EDT) Monday to
the four-party Cabinet and the Assembly created as part of a
landmark 1998 peace agreement that envisioned a Catholic-Protestant
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ''We hope these institutions will take root,'' Ulster Unionist
Party leader David Trimble said Monday during a news conference at
Stormont, the government's Belfast headquarters. ''Certainly, for
our part we will do everything we can to maximize the opportunity
here for people.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the second time in six months that Britain has ended its
27 years of direct rule and returned power to local hands.
</P>
<P>
   The Ulster Unionists' narrow approval Saturday of a return to
Catholic-Protestant power-sharing cleared the way for Britain to
restore the administrative authority it suspended in February just
11 weeks into its existence.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's top minister for Northern Ireland, Peter Mandelson,
suspended the power-sharing administration -- launched in December --
after the Irish Republican Army refused to make any disarmament
commitments.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA broke the impasse three weeks ago, promising to begin
putting its weapons ''beyond use'' -- a euphemism for disarming -- if
power-sharing resumed.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Trimble narrowly managed to persuade his badly
divided party to give the IRA a chance to live up to its pledge.
</P>
<P>
   After the vote, Trimble warned the IRA that it must deliver.
</P>
<P>
   Seamus Mallon, leader of the province's major Catholic party,
the pacifist Social Democratic and Labor Party, warned of
disastrous consequences if the newly restored administration wasn't
able to survive.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the toleration of people on the ground wouldn't wear
it again,'' said Mallon, the most senior Catholic in the newly
restored Cabinet. ''The credibility factor would be destroyed if
there was another cessation of the institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Trimble and Mallon met Monday to prepare for the second transfer
of power. The full Cabinet was scheduled to meet Thursday to get
back to work.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Northern Ireland's unlikely local coalition succeeds
will depend largely on IRA actions.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA-allied Sinn Fein party declined to speculate on when the
IRA would begin to reveal any of its secret weapons dumps to
international inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities must also deal with reforming Northern Ireland's
police force and with potentially divisive questions such as
whether to fly Britain's Union Jack flag over government buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Martin McGuinness, reputedly a former IRA chief of staff, said
he was hopeful that political leaders would make the new authority
stick this time.
</P>
<P>
   ''Political leaders need to reflect the reality that there is a
great opportunity for us all,'' said McGuinness, who is due to
resume work as Sinn Fein's education minister in the Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to build a future for everybody. The question is, are
we up to that task? I think we are. I think we can get this
right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-30-00 0154 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000530.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 02:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arson Eyed in Abortion Clinic Fire  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- Investigators say a weekend fire that
damaged an abortion clinic likely was the work of an arsonist.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities had no suspects in the blaze that broke out at 10
p.m. Sunday at the Concord Feminist Health Center. The center was
closed at the time, but damage was estimated at several thousand
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators hadn't pinpointed what caused the fire, but police
Lt. Paul Murphy said Monday that it was probably set.
</P>
<P>
   ''Given the nature of the facility the probability is fairly
high that it was targeted, as opposed to having been just ...
random,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Police were stationed at the clinic Monday, which was closed for
the Memorial Day holiday. It was uncertain when the clinic would
reopen.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second fire at the clinic, which also has been a site
of frequent protests.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1989 a fire was set the night the U.S. Supreme Court
upheld a Missouri law prohibiting abortions from being performed at
public facilities or by government employees. There was only minor
damage and the arsonist never was caught.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
