<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lazio, though new to national spotlight, is old hand at politics  </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAY SHORE, N.Y. (AP) -- He certainly didn't have the regal
political upbringing of a Kennedy, a Bush, or even Al Gore, but in
his own way, Rep. Rick Lazio appears to have spent much of his life
preparing for his moment.
</P>
<P>
   The son of an aide to a Suffolk County Republican chairman,
Enrico Anthony Lazio has burst onto the national media scene,
picking up the torch after ailing New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
dropped out of the U.S. Senate race against Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But the path to political stardom for the little-known,
four-term congressman and former county legislator winds back at
least three decades. Old friends remember Lazio, 42, as always
serious and always interested in politics.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rick was kind of born into the political process,'' said Edwin
''Buzz'' Schwenk, the former Suffolk GOP chairman who recalls a
teen-age Lazio attending Republican functions with his parents in
the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ''He'd be there on Election Night, running around with chalk in
hand, putting the vote totals up on the blackboard, doing whatever
was needed,'' Schwenk said.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's father, Anthony Lazio, was an aide to Schwenk,
responsible for organizing fund-raisers that brought such GOP
heavyweights as Ronald Reagan, John Connolly and Spiro Agnew into
Suffolk County.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rick picked this up from his father,'' Schwenk said. ''Seeing
all this as a youngster, that was kind of how it happened, I
suppose.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Suffolk County Executive John V.N. Klein also said his
earliest memories of the younger Lazio were ''being in tow with
Tony'' at GOP functions.
</P>
<P>
   ''Had I known he was someday going to be a U.S. Senate
candidate, I might have treated him better back then,'' Klein
joked.
</P>
<P>
   A 1976 graduate of West Islip High School, Lazio went on to
Vassar College in Poughkeepsie, then American University Law School
in Washington, D.C. He joined the Suffolk County district
attorney's office in 1983, staying five years before moving into
private practice.
</P>
<P>
   He ran for a seat on the Suffolk County Legislature in 1989 and
beat Democrat Thomas Downey in the 1992 Congressional election, a
victory over an 18-year incumbent that made Lazio a star in Long
Island politics.
</P>
<P>
   Colton Johnson, who as dean at Vassar knew Lazio, said he's not
surprised Lazio gravitated to a career in public service.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would have seemed entirely likely from the guy I knew
here,'' he said. ''I had no doubt when I saw him the other day
(announcing his Senate candidacy) that he was one of ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said that despite Vassar's ''image as a quite liberal
institution,'' there also is a tradition of conservative thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ''For many years, we've published a conservative journal,''
Johnson said, although he could not recall if Lazio ever
contributed.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Kittrie, a professor at the American University School
of Law, described Lazio as ''serious-minded'' and ''deliberate.''
Kittrie said Lazio has the habit of keeping up contacts -- a skill
for any good politician.
</P>
<P>
   ''Once or twice, I'd be on a shuttle to New York when all of a
sudden I'd hear his cheerful voice,'' Kittrie said. ''He always
comes over and chats with me, something that I think shows that he
obviously cares about people.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Cohen, the chief assistant district attorney in Suffolk
County, recalled his colleague as ''an excellent prosecutor.''
Lazio worked in the DA's rackets bureau, helped craft anti-crime
legislation and became spokesman for the DA's office, a role that
put him on television announcing indictments or convictions.
</P>
<P>
   One of Lazio's best friends is Manhattan attorney Mike
Moriarity. The two met in law school, and Moriarity introduced
Lazio to his sister, Patricia Moriarity, who became the
congressman's wife.
</P>
<P>
   Moriarity says that as a student, Lazio was a serious guy who
''always knew where he wanted to go'' -- into political life. Even
then, Moriarity said, ''he knew he wanted to be a local
prosecutor.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio also had another youthful experience -- courtesy of his
parents, both World War II veterans -- that would prepare him for a
politician's regular chore.
</P>
<P>
   ''They would always take him to the Memorial Day parades, the
Veterans Day parades,'' Moriarity said. ''He's very comfortable
with interacting with veterans and veterans' organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwenk, the former GOP boss, said Lazio's father, who died in
1985, would be his son's biggest cheerleader today.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think his father would be jumping through hoops, going
bananas,'' Schwenk said. ''He'd be so overjoyed at this -- a thrill
times a hundred.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Lazio campaign: http://www.lazio.com
</P>
<P>
   Clinton campaign: http://www.hillary2000.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
