<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Begins Trip to Europe  </HEADLINE>
By ANNE GEARAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton's trip to Europe this week
begins with political consultations in Portugal and ends a
continent away in Ukraine, a former Soviet republic still trying to
shake off the economic and social legacies of communism.
</P>
<P>
   In between, Clinton collects a statesmanship prize in Germany
and engages in summitry in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton left Washington on Monday night for Lisbon, Portugal,
where he was meeting with the president and prime minister today.
Clinton planned to spend three days in Portugal, which holds the
European Union's rotating presidency. He also was scheduled to
address researchers, scientists and students at a science park.
</P>
<P>
   Finding ways to enhance Internet commerce and containing the
spread of AIDS, especially in Africa, will top the agenda of talks
between Clinton and Portuguese officials.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal has long experience working on the AIDS problem in
Africa through its five former colonies there, Angola, Mozambique,
Guinea-Bissau, Cape Verde, and Sao Tome and Principe.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration recently announced it now regards the
world AIDS epidemic, which is particularly acute in Africa, as a
threat to U.S. national security.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Clinton will attend a summit meeting of the United
States and the European Union at Queluz Palace outside Lisbon.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will continue our work with our European allies for peace
and freedom to make their sacrifice matter,'' Clinton said during
Memorial Day observances Monday at Arlington National Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton noted that his trip marks the first visit of an American
president to Berlin since the city became the capital of a unified
Germany and the first time an American president will address a
democratically elected legislature in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ''The world of today would not be recognized by those who lived
at the beginning of the Cold War,'' Clinton said. ''Old adversaries
have become allies, dictatorships have become democracies. Europe
is more peaceful and united, the communism we fought to contain has
collapsed, reformed or been discredited around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   In Aachen, Germany, Clinton will be awarded the International
Charlemagne Prize, presented annually to a person who has worked
toward European unity. In Berlin he will attend with leaders of a
dozen other countries a summit on ''third way'' politics hosted by
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder. The idea is to consider alternatives
to the traditional liberal and conservative approaches to
government.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will journey on to Russia for weekend talks with the new
president, Vladimir Putin, and then travel June 5 to the Ukraine
for a meeting with President Leonid Kuchma before departing for
Washington that night.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has been lowering expectations for the Russian
summit, saying Clinton does not expect to win any new arms control
agreements. However, White House officials have emphasized that
Clinton is president through the rest of this year and have
rejected George W. Bush's request that Clinton refrain from signing
an arms control pact before he leaves office. Bush is the
presumptive GOP presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton touched on the national security implications of his
visit Monday, but also put change in Russia in more sweeping
context.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will visit Russia, our former adversary with whom we are
trying so hard to build a new partnership and a safer world,''
Clinton said at Arlington. ''Russia has just seen its first
transition from one democratically elected government to another in
a thousand years of history.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
