<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourists Lobby for Capitol Tours  </HEADLINE>
By JANELLE CARTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Ah, the signs that summer is near: blooming
flowers, sunny skies, hurried lawmakers and, of course, tourists.
At the U.S. Capitol, after all, tourists are as much a springtime
rite as the annual budget battles.
</P>
<P>
   So it's no wonder when Capitol administrators moved to cut back
visitors' hours in the historic building, lobbyists representing
tour operators got to work.
</P>
<P>
   The result was an agreement reached earlier this month that
keeps the Capitol open in the evening until June 15, when the peak
period of mostly student visitors ends.
</P>
<P>
   ''It created the biggest brouhaha I've ever had in terms of
personal interest and response,'' said former Nevada Rep. Jim
Santini, now a lobbyist for the Lexington, Ky.-based National Tour
Association, which represents 4,000 tour operators.
</P>
<P>
   NTA President Mark Hoffmann said the victory shows ''the effect
of grass-roots lobbying efforts by NTA members.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1997, the Capitol had been open from 9 a.m. to 8 p.m. from
March 1 to Aug. 31 to accommodate the peak tourist season in
Washington. During the other months, the Capitol closes to tours at
4:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Officials figured that the later hours would help ease tourist
congestion by spreading tours throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   But in February, the Capitol Management Board decided to close
the Capitol at 6 p.m. during the peak season both as a cost-saving
measure and after noticing a drop in late evening tours.
</P>
<P>
   ''The number of people taking advantage of the 6 to 8 period
wasn't nearly as big as the number during the prime hours,'' said
Ted Daniel, director of the Capitol Guide Service. Prime hours are
between 9 a.m. and 4:30 p.m. when between 10,000 to 15,000 tourists
enter the Capitol, Daniel said.
</P>
<P>
   But that was when tour operators mobilized.
</P>
<P>
   Santini sprang into action soon after receiving a call from a
concerned operator in late February and launched what he calls ''a
pretty aggressive grass-roots network appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   They visited congressional offices. They wrote letters. They
made phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   ''Congressmen said 'We didn't know it was shut down.' Not only
did we not get any notice, nobody received any notice,'' Santini
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tour operators argued that closing the Capitol early would
affect more than 38,000 visitors expected to take advantage of the
6 p.m. to 8 p.m. time slot during May and June.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most importantly, thousands of students visit the
Capitol, particularly during the months of April, May and June, as
part of their civics classes and many of those groups have had
their itineraries planned for months, Santini said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It seemed to me an imperative that certainly during this peak
period of visitation to do everything we could to accommodate the
nation's students in their opportunity to learn and to study
firsthand the seat of government,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with the management board, which included the
Senate and House sergeant at arms along with the Capitol architect,
a compromise was reached to keep the Capitol open until 8 p.m.
during the week until June 15.
</P>
<P>
   Administrators will examine the visitor numbers to determine
whether later hours are needed next year.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's perfect,'' teacher Ron Miller said of the Capitol visit.
His students from the Archer School for Girls in Los Angeles get to
see firsthand ''all the historic events that took place that formed
our nation and how important it is we have a judicial system.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
