<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Briton Heads for N. Pole in Balloon  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   OSLO, Norway (AP) -- A British adventurer floated over the polar
ice cap Monday in a bid to be the first person to fly over the
North Pole in a balloon, his supporters said.
</P>
<P>
   David Hempelman-Adams, 44, lifted off from Longyearbyen, the
main town on Norway's Svalbard islands, on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The greatest fear is to have to land in the Arctic Ocean,'' he
was quoted as telling the Oslo newspaper Dagbladet before he took
off. He said there would be little chance of surviving a crash in
the icy waters he has now successfully flown over.
</P>
<P>
   The first attempt to fly in a balloon from Svalbard to the North
Pole, in 1897, ended in tragedy for a Swedish expedition when the
three flyers died after three months on the ice when their balloon
crashed.
</P>
<P>
   Hempelman-Adams told the newspaper that he hoped to complete the
600-mile solo flight in about four days in the 80-foot-tall helium
balloon. From there, he would either land or attempt to fly on to
Canada, depending on wind conditions.
</P>
<P>
   One of his greatest challenges will be to withstand temperatures
down to 76 degrees below zero as he rides in an open wicker basket.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-30-00 0218 </TRAILER>
