<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Forces Leave Eritrea Areas  </HEADLINE>
By ANDREW ENGLAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) -- Ethiopia said it withdrew its
forces today from parts of Eritrea captured along the western
front, saying Ethiopian troops had achieved their goals and had no
interest in holding on to the territory.
</P>
<P>
   The western front is only one of three areas where Ethiopia and
Eritrea have fought along their poorly demarcated border. Ethiopia
launched a punishing offensive May 12 along all fronts to take back
territory Eritrea captured earlier in the 2-year-old war.
</P>
<P>
   Selome Taddesse, Ethiopia's government spokeswoman, said that
after destroying the Eritrean army and recovering occupied
territory on the western front, Ethiopia troops had been withdrawn.
There has been no fighting along the western front for several
days.
</P>
<P>
   ''After successfully achieving their mission, the heroic
Ethiopian defense forces that had been controlling western Eritrea
since May 12 have withdrawn,'' Selome said. ''As the Ethiopian
government has reiterated on numerous occasions, it has no interest
in occupying sovereign Eritrean territory and, having achieved its
goals, it has withdrawn its troops accordingly.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreign ministers from both sides are expected to participate in
indirect peace talks today in Algeria to find a permanent solution
to the border dispute that has cost tens of thousands of lives.
Ethiopian Foreign Minister Seyoum Mesfin's late arrival Monday in
Algiers forced their postponement.
</P>
<P>
   In Asmara on Monday, four Ethiopian MiG-23s swept in over the
international airport at midday, unleashing rockets and then bombs
on a military airstrip just west of the commercial runways.
</P>
<P>
   Two Eritrean MiG's took off in pursuit, with flames and black
and white smoke billowing into the sky.
</P>
<P>
   Two civilians were wounded in the attack, said Eritrean
presidential spokesman Yemene Gebremeskel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
