<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 a.m.  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tuesday, May 30, 2000 
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Begins Trip to Europe
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton's trip to Europe this week begins with
political consultations in Portugal and ends a continent away in Ukraine, a
former Soviet republic still trying to shake off the economic and social
legacies of communism. In between, Clinton collects a statesmanship prize in
Germany and engages in summitry in Russia. Clinton left Washington on Monday
night for Lisbon, Portugal, where he was meeting with the president and prime
minister Tuesday. Clinton planned to spend three days in Portugal.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fujimori Defends Claim to 3rd Term
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- Facing international pressure after his lopsided
re-election victory, President Alberto Fujimori went on national television to
defend his claim to a third term in office. Without identifying to whom he was
referring, Fujimori said in the appearance late Monday that there had been a
campaign to "satanize" the electoral process and to "misinform and disorient the
citizenry." He reiterated that the election was fair and said he hoped he would
not disappoint Peruvians "in initiating a more authentic democracy" in his next
five years in power.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
N. Ireland Regains a Measure of Self-Rule
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Northern Ireland regained a measure of
self-rule Tuesday, giving the province's Protestant and Catholic leaders another
chance to achieve a lasting peace. Britain handed back powers at midnight (7:00
p.m. EDT) Monday to the four-party Cabinet and the Assembly created as part of a
landmark 1998 peace agreement that envisioned a Catholic-Protestant
administration. This is the second time in six months that Britain has ended its
27 years of direct rule and returned power to local hands.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mori's Popularity Plunges Further
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- Support for Japan's prime minister hit a new low Tuesday,
making him the least popular prime minister in decades to lead this country's
ruling party into parliamentary elections. Support for Prime Minister Yoshiro
Mori's government has dropped to just 19 percent, according to a new poll by the
Asahi, a major Japanese newspaper. The poll, conducted by telephone Sunday and
Monday, showed Mori's support rating had fallen from 41 percent just a month
earlier.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
US Won't Pressure Taiwan Over Talks
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- The United States will not pressure Taiwan to accept
China's conditions for talks between the two rivals, the top U.S. representative
in Taiwan said Monday. The comments by Raymond Burghardt, director of the
American Institute in Taiwan, were apparently aimed at calming Taiwanese who
fear that Washington might team up with Beijing and try to force Taiwan to the
bargaining table. New Taiwanese President Chen Shui-bian has offered to meet
with Chinese leaders.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Army: 44 Die in Indonesia Violence
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- At least 44 people were killed in an armed raid
on a mostly Christian village in the eastern Indonesian province of North
Maluku, an army chief said Tuesday. North Maluku military chief. Lt. Col.
Sukarwo said suspected Muslim militants attacked the village on Halmahera island
before dawn on Monday. In addition to the 44 killed in the attack, at least 102
people were injured. Sukarwo said the military believed the attackers came from
a neighboring island and were members of a Muslim fighting force known as Lasker
Jihad, or Holy War Troops.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
L.A. Police Chief's Kin Shot Dead
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A gunman who shot and killed the granddaughter of Los
Angeles Police Chief Bernard C. Parks has yet to be apprehended. Lori Gonzalez,
20, was shot several times by the gunman, who walked up and opened fire on the
car in the driveway of a Popeye's chicken stand in the city's South Central area
on Sunday night, Lt. Horace Frank said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Moderate Quake Shakes Central Taiwan
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- A moderate earthquake shook central Taiwan on
Tuesday, seismologists said. There were no immediate reports of damage or
casualties. The 4.3-magnitude quake struck a mountainous area 10 miles east of
Sun Moon Lake, a popular resort and the island's largest natural lake, the
Central Weather Bureau said. A 7.6-magnitude quake devastated the region in
September, killing 2,400 people and destroying thousands of homes.
</P>
