<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 09:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State holiday sought to remember Harriet Tubman  </HEADLINE>
By HADLEY PAWLAK
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- In ceremonies across New York state Monday,
Harriet Tubman was remembered as a Civil War nurse, scout and spy
for the Union Army who helped hundreds of slaves find freedom.
</P>
<P>
   And while Tubman does not have official veteran status, veterans
here saluted her likeness on the Women Veteran's Memorial and
joined the call for a state holiday honoring the heroine.
</P>
<P>
   ''Harriet Tubman is long overdue for honors from the state in
which she lived and where she is buried,'' reads a letter calling
on state officials to adopt a bill making March 10 ''Harriet Tubman
Day.''
</P>
<P>
   She ''devoted her life to the realization of the American credo,
'Liberty and Justice for all,''' the letter reads.
</P>
<P>
   Memorial Day gatherings in Queens, Syracuse, Binghamton, Buffalo
and the Bronx also celebrated the life of Tubman, who earned the
nickname ''Moses'' for her pivotal role in leading slaves to the
Underground Railroad -- a secret escape route used before the Civil
War.
</P>
<P>
   Aided by thousands of ''conductors'' who helped escapees get
from one hide-out to another on their way north, more than 100,000
slaves are estimated to have met freedom through the Underground
Railroad.
</P>
<P>
   State Assembly Deputy Speaker Arthur O. Eve, D-Buffalo, and
State Sen. Michael Nozzolio, R-Seneca Falls, have sponsored bills
calling for a Harriet Tubman state holiday.
</P>
<P>
   In Albany Monday, James Howe of the 369th Veterans' Association,
an association of black veterans named after the all black unit
that served in World War I, presented state officials with a stack
of petitions signed by 10,000 people calling for the March 10
holiday.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is thicker than the Manhattan phone book,'' Howe said,
''and on Tuesday we've got five more volumes going to the
governor's office.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the governor's office did not immediately return
a call seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, the measure would make Harriet Tubman day the 13th
official state holiday and the most recent since Martin Luther King
Jr. Day was created in 1985 in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Bachmann of the Women's Building, a feminist organization,
said an official day honoring Tubman would also be the first
holiday in the country named for a woman.
</P>
<P>
   ''She was a brave woman who deserves the necessary recognition
that other historic figures have had,'' Bachmann said. ''With
10,000 signatures of people calling for this, it can't be too long
before politicians feel pressure to pass it.''
</P>
<P>
   A pamphlet produced in support of the holiday by the Black
Women's Leadership Caucus describes Tubman as the first woman to
serve in active duty in the Armed Services and calls her the only
woman in American history to lead an armed attack during a state of
war.
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Smith, vice president of the Black Nurses Association,
said Tubman was much more than a ''relentless and fearless
soldier,'' explaining how she created a nursing home in upstate New
York to care for freed slaves who fell ill.
</P>
<P>
   ''I treat her as a mentor and role model; a woman of distinction
who I strive to emulate,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   A day in Tubman's honor would be a celebration of ''freedom,
justice and equality,'' said Hayley Eaddy, who attended the Albany
commemoration.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's a woman who had a major role in the building and
reconstruction of America.''	   
</P>
<P>
   Tubman died March 10, 1913 and is buried in Auburn, 23 miles
west of Syracuse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
