<HEADLINE> Out-of-state buyers snapping up vacation homes  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Aging baby boomers and beneficiaries of a strong
economy are
reviving the sale of second homes both in Connecticut and
nationwide.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Real estate agents say more Americans are putting their
discretionary dollars into a vacation home and properties aren't
lasting long on the market as both demand and prices rise.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're getting several e-mails a day from people looking for
second homes,'' said Litchfield agent Frank Moss, of Landmark Real
Estate Co. ''We went through a pretty slow period 10 years ago when
nothing was moving. Today, it's booming.''
</P>
<P>
   Moss said a couple from New Jersey recently walked into his
Goshen office and paid $695,000 -- in cash -- for a three-bedroom
vacation home on Woodridge Lake. A week later a New York couple
paid the $995,000 asking price for a Litchfield Hills weekend home.
</P>
<P>
   Property also is at a premium on the Connecticut shoreline.
</P>
<P>
   ''Years ago the majority of our buyers were coming down Route 9
from Hartford. But we are seeing more and more people coming up the
coast'' from New York, New Jersey and Fairfield County, said Sue
DiMeo, shoreline regional manager for William Raveis Home-Link in
Old Saybrook. ''We have a lot of land here and people are beginning
to discover it.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the second-home market has increased 9.3 percent since
1997, with 377,000 second homes purchased in 1999, according to the
National Association of Realtors.
</P>
<P>
   In Connecticut, demand is outpacing supply and driving up the
prices.
</P>
<P>
   The median sales price of a home in Madison, for example, was
$245,000 in 1999, 20 percent higher than in 1995. In Guilford, the
$210,000 median sales price of homes last year was an 18 percent
increase from 1995, and in Essex, the $207,000 median sales price
of homes in 1999 was 15 percent higher than 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, the median sales price of second homes was $127,800
in 1999, a 29 percent increase since 1989, according to the
National Association of Realtors.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller summer shoreline cottages have been snapped up and razed
to make way for half-million dollar, year-round second homes. For
example, on Maple Avenue in the Knollwood Beach section of Old
Saybrook, almost every fifth house is under renovation.
</P>
<P>
   ''If someone called and wanted a fixer-upper in the early 1990s
they had their pick. Not anymore,'' said agent Arlene Soden.
''There is absolutely nothing left.''
</P>
<P>
   The Corwin family of New York recently settled on a vacation
home in Madison after years of vacationing in the Hamptons and Cape
Cod.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were so sick of it,'' Pamela D'Arc Corwin said of the
crowds in the Hamptons. ''Everything was difficult. Getting into a
restaurant. Going to the movies. Unless you planned far in advance,
you didn't get to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ''We spent one year on the Cape, and trying to get back and
forth was impossible,'' she said. ''One time it took my husband 10
hours to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Their $350,000 four-bedroom Madison home has views of the water
and beach rights.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now we couldn't imagine going anywhere else,'' Corwin said.
''It's the perfect amount of time from the city. It's easy. It's
filled with kids. It's a real community with a real neighborhood.
To me, it's paradise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
