<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Stays Out of Medicare Fight  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE ASSEO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today stayed out of a
dispute between the federal government and 181 hospitals that say
they were underpaid for care they provided to particularly
high-cost Medicare patients.
</P>
<P>
   The court, without comment, turned away the hospitals' argument
that federal law sets a minimum payment for such high-cost
patients. Their appeal said the government underpaid hospitals
nationwide by $342 million during fiscal 1985 and 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Further underpayments through the 1990s might total $3 billion,
the hospitals contend.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare, which has provided health insurance for the elderly
since 1965, was overhauled in 1983 to reimburse hospitals at fixed
rates based partly on the hospital's location and the type of
illness treated.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare pays extra for patients whose treatment is particularly
expensive. Federal law says the payments must be 5 percent to 6
percent of the total projected payments for that year.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Health and Human Services has interpreted that
to mean such estimates are to be made at the beginning of a fiscal
year, but the final amounts may turn out to be more or less than 5
percent to 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The supplemental amount for fiscal 1985 was 3 percent of the
total payment and 4.4 percent in fiscal 1986. The hospitals said
that meant hospitals nationwide were shortchanged by $241 million
in 1985 and $101 million the following year.
</P>
<P>
   The hospitals contended the law requires the government to
adjust the payments at the end of the year. After the government
refused to do so, the hospitals sued.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge ruled in January 1998 the law did require such
retroactive payments but said the government properly used 1981
data to set reimbursement rates for 1985 and 1986.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia
reversed on both questions.
</P>
<P>
   The law on the percent 5 to 6 percent payment is unclear, said
the court in deferring to the government's decision that
retroactive payments were not required. However, the court ordered
the government to either explain why 1984 data were not used to set
reimbursement rates, or to recalculate those rates.
</P>
<P>
   In the appeal acted on today, the hospitals' lawyers said the
law was clear and the appeals court should not have deferred to the
government's interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department lawyers said the appeal was premature.
</P>
<P>
   The case is Los Angeles County vs. Shalala, 99-1421.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: For the appeals court ruling:
http://www.uscourts.gov/links.html and click on District of
Columbia Circuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-30-00 1013 </TRAILER>
