<HEADLINE> Dow Gains 82; Nasdaq Climbs 104  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were sharply higher in early trading
today as investors returned from a three-day weekend ready to look
for bargains. Technology and telecom stocks led the gains.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 82.25 at 10,381.49.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Nasdaq composite
index was up 104.85 at 3,309.96, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was up 16.68 at 1,394.70.
</P>
<P>
   The telecommunications sector received a lift from the news that
France Telecom is buying Britain's Orange from Vodafone Air Touch
PLC for about $37.6 billion in cash and stock.
</P>
<P>
   France Telecom shares rose 7\ to 138\ on the New York Stock
Exchange, and Vodafone Air Touch rose 3 3/16 to 45 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   The deal raised speculation that more global mergers will follow
in the telecom industry. Alcatel rose 6 1/16 to 55 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of high-tech industry leaders also rose. Sun Microsystems
rose 3\ to 76{ and Cisco Systems rose 2} to 57 11/16.
</P>
<P>
   Traders attributed the gains to bargain-hunting. Many
high-profile technology stocks have been under pressure in the past
two weeks as investors have wondered whether their future earnings
will justify their relatively high share prices. Most analysts
expect rising interest rates to eventually take a toll on corporate
earnings as it become more expensive to borrow money to finance
growth.
</P>
<P>
   Technology companies could be hurt if their old-economy clients
curb spending on technology while they weather rising interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks rose despite an economic report that suggested six rate
increases by the Federal Reserve in the past year have not yet
sapped consumer sentiment. Consumer confidence jumped sharply in
May, approaching the all-time high it reached in January, the
Conference Board said.
</P>
<P>
   Traders were choosing to gloss over the consumer confidence
report and look ahead to a pair of reports due out later this week.
On Thursday, the National Association of Purchasing Management will
issue a report on activity in the industrial economy during May.
And on Friday, the Labor Department will issue its May employment
report.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 2-to-1 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 105.49 million
shares, ahead of Friday's sluggish pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index rose 7.35 to 464.72.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average slipped 0.1 percent.
European indexes were mostly higher. Germany's DAX index was up 1.7
percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 2.2 percent, and France's
CAC-40 was up 1.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
