<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 11:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court To Study Maritime Rules  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD CARELLI
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court said Tuesday it will use a
dispute from Illinois to resolve what the justices were told are
conflicting legal rules for maritime businesses on different
stretches of the Mississippi River.
</P>
<P>
   The court said it will decide whether a man who says he hurt his
back while working on a ship can sue the ship's owner in state
court even though the owner previously filed a federal lawsuit
seeking to limit its liability for the accident.
</P>
<P>
   James Lewis was a resident of Madison County, Ill., when on
March 17, 1998, he allegedly hurt his back while working as a
deckhand on the M/V Karen Michelle. The ship is owned by Lewis &AMP;
Clark Marine Inc., which is based in Granite City, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   A week after the accident, Lewis &AMP; Clark Marine filed a federal
lawsuit seeking to limit its liability for the accident to no more
than $450,000, the ship's stated worth. The lawsuit, filed with a
federal trial judge in Missouri, invoked the federal Limitation of
Liability Act, which allows shipowners to seek such limits and to
select the court.
</P>
<P>
   About a week later, Lewis sued the shipping company in an
Illinois state court. He alleged that Lewis &AMP; Clark Marine was
negligent and that the ship was not seaworthy.
</P>
<P>
   After being informed of Lewis' state court lawsuit, the federal
judge dismissed the limitation lawsuit that had been filed by the
shipping company.
</P>
<P>
   But the 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reversed the judge's
decision, and ruled that the federal trial judge should proceed
with the case.
</P>
<P>
   In the appeal acted on today, Lewis' lawyer said the appeals
court's ruling conflicts with those of other federal appeals
courts.
</P>
<P>
   ''As a result,'' argued Roy Dripps of Wood River, Ill.,
''vessels plying the Mississippi River cross into a different set
of maritime rules when they pass into Mississippi from Arkansas.''
</P>
<P>
   The appeal said the 8th Circuit court's ruling ''erected a
conflicting set of maritime rules over the country's primary inland
waterway which vary, not with the behavior of the parties, but with
the location of the vessel within a particular (judicial)
circuit.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Lewis &AMP; Clark Maritime had urged the justices to
reject Lewis' appeal.
</P>
<P>
   They called the appeals court's ruling ''a straightforward
application of traditional and unremarkable principles of maritime
law to a non-traditional situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The case is Lewis vs. Lewis &AMP; Clark Maritime Inc., 99-1331.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: For the appeals court ruling in Lewis and Clark
Maritime v. Lewis: http://www.uscourts.gov/links.html and click on
8th Circuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
