<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 11:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York GOP prepares to nominate little-known congressman as Giuliani sub </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Promising to take his campaign against
Hillary Rodham Clinton ''block by block'' and ''house by house,''
Rep. Rick Lazio today prepared to accept the U.S. Senate nomination
of Republican leaders gathered in Buffalo for their state
convention.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll be in every county, in every community and in every
neighborhood,'' the little-known congressman from Long Island told
reporters before breakfast with a small group of supporters at a
Buffalo restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's withdrawal from the race just 11 days
ago to deal with prostate cancer opened the door for the
boyish-looking, four-term congressman. His candidacy was quickly
supported by Gov. George Pataki and other Republican leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a true hometown boy versus somebody from another state,''
said state GOP Chairman William Powers, stressing a favorite
Republican theme used against Clinton -- that she had never lived in
the state before moving to New York in January -- on the eve of the
party's nominating convention.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's formal nomination was to come late this afternoon at a
Buffalo hotel, a far cry from the sports arena in Albany that
Democrats packed with more than 10,000 people earlier this month as
they nominated the first lady for the seat being vacated by her
fellow Democrat, Daniel Patrick Moynihan.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll have more than 2,000 people, which for us is great,''
Powers said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the hotel this morning, more than 200 state prison
guards protested their lack of a contract with the state, seeking
to send a message to Pataki by raining on Lazio's parade.
</P>
<P>
   ''Lazio, we vote!'' the protesters chanted.
</P>
<P>
   There was little suspense for the more than 400 GOP delegates.
The congressman's own schedule, issued Sunday, stated that at 4:30
p.m. Tuesday: ''Lazio to accept nomination at the New York state
GOP Convention.''
</P>
<P>
   While Lazio lacks the star power of Clinton, he did embark on a
whirlwind pre-convention schedule that had him hitting all the
major Sunday morning news shows just one day after his formal
candidacy announcement. He then flew around the state and marched
in two Memorial Day parades on Monday before heading to a barbecue
at the Rochester-area home of Monroe County GOP Chairman Steve
Minarik.
</P>
<P>
   After staying the night in Rochester, Lazio planned a breakfast
with supporters in Buffalo this morning and a luncheon with
Republican women.
</P>
<P>
   The congressman was arriving in Buffalo literally with a
campaign battle scar. He tripped during a parade Monday on Long
Island, leaving him with a cut lip that required eight stitches.
</P>
<P>
   ''It'll be the first of a few,'' quipped Powers.
</P>
<P>
   ''With this lip it looks like I was kissing the grill,'' Lazio
joked at the Rochester barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   After being patched up, Lazio joined Giuliani in Queens for
another Memorial Day parade, their first campaign appearance
together.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's gotten off to an absolutely tremendous start, and if I
could judge by the reception here in northern Queens, he's going to
be a very very strong candidate. ... I'm going to do everything I
can to help him get elected,'' the New York City mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of that, Giuliani was skipping the GOP state convention
so as not to upstage Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   Independent polls, even before the Giuliani withdrawal, have
shown Clinton hovering in the mid-40 percentage range, a situation
that has given Republicans hope that Lazio can copy the
giant-killer role played by Pataki in 1994 when, as a little-known
state senator, he toppled three-term Democratic Gov. Mario Cuomo.
</P>
<P>
   Like Pataki, Lazio is from the suburbs surrounding New York City
and is considered a moderate Republican.
</P>
<P>
   GOP boss Powers said that while he expects a close race, he is
confident.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's represented the people of New York, like his opponent
hasn't and he's paid New York state income taxes, like his opponent
hasn't,'' the party leader said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans said they were happy to have Lazio instead of
Giuliani as their candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's now going to be an issues-oriented campaign. It's no
longer going to be a celebrity campaign,'' Monroe County Executive
Jack Doyle said at the Rochester barbecue. ''With Giuliani and Mrs.
Clinton, it was going to turn into a celebrity issue, as to who
looked better and who had more celebrity friends and who was more
famous ... I think people are a little tired of the celebrity side
of the picture.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Now that Rick's in, there's some excitement and the feeling
he's really going to put his heart and soul into this race, whereas
it seemed that the mayor wanted the office but he didn't really
want to campaign for it,'' said Larry Staub, vice chairman of the
Monroe County GOP.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
