<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 11:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Restricts Rights of Creditors  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE ASSEO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Companies that provide insurance or other
services to a business during its bankruptcy proceedings cannot try
to collect unpaid fees from collateral held by another creditor,
the Supreme Court said today.
</P>
<P>
   The unanimous ruling in a Missouri case said only bankruptcy
trustees can invoke a provision of federal bankruptcy law to
collect fees from collateral held by someone else.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Antonin Scalia wrote for the court that the law says
''the trustee'' can recover costs in such a manner, but does not
mention anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fact that the sole party named -- the trustee -- has a
unique role in bankruptcy proceedings makes it entirely plausible
that Congress would provide a power to him and not to others,''
Scalia wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The court also:
</P>
<P>
   --Declined to enter a dispute between the federal government and
181 hospitals that say they were underpaid for care they provided
to particularly high-cost Medicare patients. Without comment, the
court turned away the hospitals' argument that federal law sets a
minimum payment for such high-cost patients.
</P>
<P>
   --Refused to consider federal rules intended to keep telephone
service affordable in high-cost areas and to subsidize Internet
hookups for schools and libraries. A paging service company's
appeal was rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Ruling in a second bankruptcy case today, the justices made it
easier for governments to collect back taxes from bankrupt debtors.
In an Illinois dispute over state sales taxes owed on a $12 million
jet, the court said that if a tax law puts the burden of proof on
the taxpayer instead of the government, that burden remains the
same in bankruptcy court.
</P>
<P>
   The justices unanimously upheld a 7th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals decision that said Illinois law put the burden on William
J. Stoecker to prove he did not willfully avoid paying sales taxes
on the jet owned by his now-defunct corporation.
</P>
<P>
   In the Missouri case, the justices ruled against the Hartford
Underwriters Insurance Co.'s effort to collect unpaid premiums for
workers' compensation insurance it provided to Hen House
Interstate, which operated businesses such as service stations,
restaurants and gift stores.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Hen House sought protection from creditors in
bankruptcy court in St. Louis to allow it to reorganize under
federal bankruptcy law.
</P>
<P>
   During the bankruptcy reorganization, Hartford provided workers'
compensation insurance to Hen House, which the company needed to
continue operating. During that time, Hen House failed to pay
$51,871 in premiums.
</P>
<P>
   After the reorganization was converted to a bankruptcy
liquidation proceeding, Hartford sought to collect the premiums
from collateral held by Hen House's lender, Magna Bank. The bank
later merged into Union Planters National Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The bank argued that Hartford lacked legal standing under
bankruptcy law to seek such payment.
</P>
<P>
   A bankruptcy judge and a three-judge panel of the 8th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals ruled for Hartford, but the full 8th
Circuit court reversed and rejected Hartford's claim.
</P>
<P>
   The bankruptcy law allows only trustees, and not other parties
such as Hartford, to collect from collateral held by a secured
creditor, the full appeals court said.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court agreed today.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that provide services to firms in bankruptcy
proceedings can insist on being paid in cash, or they can contract
directly with the secured creditor, Scalia said. Also, he said,
they can ''avoid unnecessary losses simply by paying attention to
the status of their accounts.''
</P>
<P>
   The cases decided today are Hartford Underwriters Insurance Co.
vs. Union Planters National Bank, 99-409, and Raleigh vs. Illinois,
99-387.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: For current Supreme Court decisions:
http://www.supremecourtus.gov or
http://supct.law.cornell.edu/supct/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
