<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 12:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> In Atlantic City and Ocean City, lifeguard hours are being extended </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   OCEAN CITY, N.J. (AP) -- Two towns where drownings occurred last
year are extending hours for lifeguards at some beaches this year,
saying the moves may be necessary to protect swimmers.
</P>
<P>
   In Ocean City, three of the busiest beaches will remain guarded
by lifeguards on weekends until 8 p.m. -- three hours later than
usual. The beaches are Eighth Street, Ninth Street and 12th Street.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlantic City, guards will remain on the beach at Kentucky
Avenue until 8 p.m. -- two hours later -- every day of the week,
beginning in late June.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've noticed that people come later and stay later,'' said
Assistant Capt. Bud McKinley of the Ocean City Beach Patrol. ''One
thing is skin cancer is a concern for some people. Another is that
it's quieter in the evening, and aside from there being no
(lifeguard) protection, it's a pretty pleasant time to be on the
beach.''
</P>
<P>
   In both cities, after-hours drownings prompted the changes.
</P>
<P>
   On July 5, Brian K. Wilson, 34, of Philadelphia died when he
rushed into the water at the Eighth Street beach in Ocean City to
save an 8-year-old girl who had been swept out to sea by a riptide.
She survived. The incident occurred about 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   On July 7, Johnette Bailey, 32, of Atlantic City died when she
went to the aid of three young nephews struggling against a riptide
in the water at Kentucky Avenue. That incident occurred about 7
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic City Beach Patrol officials extended lifeguard hours at
the beach after the drownings and intend to do so again this year,
Chief Bob Levy said.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean City officials made the decision this year, after beach
patrol officials conducted a study that found more swimmers to be
using the ocean late in the day.
</P>
<P>
   They picked the three beaches that are closest to public
restrooms, amusement rides and hotels because those are the ones
most likely to have late-staying bathers, McKinley said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's a great idea,'' said George Browne, chairman of
the Jersey shore chapter of the Surfrider Foundation, a nonprofit
environmental organization based in San Clemente, Calif. ''A lot of
the people who come to the beach have no experience with the
currents and don't know the difference between a riptide and an
undertow.''
</P>
<P>
   The hours changes make sense for Atlantic City and Ocean City,
where day-trippers and novice swimmers are more common because of
the resort nature of the cities and the high number of rental units
or hotel rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Beach patrol officials elsewhere on the shore say they don't
need longer hours.
</P>
<P>
   ''In Stone Harbor, it's a family-oriented beach,'' said beach
patrol Lt. Rodney Tice. ''With the (cost of) beach badges, you
don't get the day people. They'll go to Wildwood. So you have more
experienced people swimming here.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Unger, a spokesman for the Surfers Environmental Alliance,
says beach patrols are mistaken if they believe they can wipe out
drownings entirely.
</P>
<P>
   ''New Jersey beach towns have this mentality that they can
control nature and control people with 100 percent safety. It's
unrealistic, and it's counterproductive. You have to have more
respect for the ocean, that's all,'' Unger said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-30-00 1230 </TRAILER>
