<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> $10M project to rebuild blocks plagued by fires  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- In a two-block area of abandoned
buildings, many of them blighted further by fire, business and
community groups are conducting a $10.8 million experiment in
revitalization.
</P>
<P>
   The project will build homes in the section of the Frog Hollow
neighborhood where previously police found drinkers and drug
dealers. Residents believe the abandoned buildings attracted
troublemakers, who are blamed for many of the two dozen fires in
the last three years, community activist Jose Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who has worked to rid Frog Hollow of blighted
buildings for 10 years, called the makeover long overdue. It's the
most important step, he said, in rejuvenating an area that was once
beautiful and safe.
</P>
<P>
   ''This will be a great achievement, especially since it's so
close to Burns School,'' said Martinez, chairman of the
Mortson/Putnam Heights Project committee. ''It will change the face
of the neighborhood and hopefully put an end to all the problems
those abandoned buildings brought.''
</P>
<P>
   Most properties on the two blocks -- not far from the state
Capitol -- are vacant, and owners are frequently behind on property
taxes. Empty lots mar the stretch of street.
</P>
<P>
   Plans call for renovating or building 42 owner-occupied one- and
two-family homes and 22 rental units on 29 properties. David A.
Mesite, director of development with Broad-Park Development Corp.,
a nonprofit group that is a partner in the project, has been
working with city officials to buy foreclosed buildings and lots
that are now city-owned.
</P>
<P>
   The ownership is targeted at moderate-income people who might
not be able to afford a home, but is not limited to first-time
homeowners, Mesite said.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents say they fear that they'll be left out of the
plan or that the work will price them out of rentals. Mesite says
there will be safeguards to protect renters.
</P>
<P>
   Evelyn Welgoss, whose three-bedroom rental is not among the
buildings designated for development, is eager to apply to become a
homeowner for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is what we've been waiting for,'' said the 38-year-old
secretary who was burned out of another apartment in the
neighborhood seven years ago. ''It looks like we've survived the
bad times.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-30-00 1312 </TRAILER>
