<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> At the Movies: 'Running Free'  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID GERMAIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   What a disastrous decision by the filmmakers to tell their
equine tale ''Running Free'' straight from the horse's mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Or rather, the horse's mind. This story of an orphaned colt's
adventures in Africa has some lovely visuals, but whatever the
family film had going for it is undermined by absurd, droning,
unnecessary narration, a human voice relating the horse's
none-too-interesting thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   What's next, talking dinosaurs?
</P>
<P>
   ''Running Free'' tells the story of Lucky, a horse born at sea
in 1914 aboard a ship carrying workhorses from Europe to an African
mining town. Lucky is separated from his mother, befriended by a
stable boy, bullied by a thoroughbred stallion, and ultimately
abandoned with the other horses when World War I forces the humans
to evacuate.
</P>
<P>
   The narration, with Lukas Haas providing Lucky's musings, kicks
in at the starting gate, and proceeds from cloying to aggravating
to downright exasperating by the movie's end.
</P>
<P>
   Does anyone, viewing the wrenching image of a helpless foal
parted from its mom by careless humans, really need to hear the
young horse blandly asking, ''Why didn't they understand that I
needed to be with my mother?''
</P>
<P>
   As Lucky flees alone into the desert, is anyone really
illuminated by his pronouncement, ''It was time for me to set out
into an unknown world, where I would be as wild and free as in my
dreams''?
</P>
<P>
   Are Lucky's sad face and images of him wandering alone among
endless sand dunes insufficient to convey his solitude, or must the
filmmakers have the horse whine, ''I started to feel lonely''?
</P>
<P>
   ''Running Free'' has a terminal case of open mouth, insert hoof.
</P>
<P>
   A mute button may be the answer. Russian director Sergei Bodrov
and producer Jean-Jacques Annaud (''The Name of the Rose,'' ''The
Bear'') visually captured all the elements to propel the story,
without the narration.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky's voice-overs may be a concession to young children, who
might have squirmed in their seats if they had to watch a whole
movie without words. But they're likely to be just as bored with
the talking version, which plays out like a child's picture book,
Haas' staccato narration subbing for parents reading along with
their youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than shelling out for ''Running Free,'' adults would be
better off pulling a picture book off the shelves, parking the kids
on their laps, and letting the children hear a story in their
parents' voices.
</P>
<P>
   ''Running Free,'' distributed by Sony, is rated G and runs 82
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
</P>
<P>
   G -- General audiences. All ages admitted.
</P>
<P>
   PG -- Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 -- Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
</P>
<P>
   R -- Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
</P>
<P>
   NC-17 -- No one under 17 admitted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-30-00 1336 </TRAILER>
