<HEADLINE> Aid Mission to Lithuania To Close  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States plans to close its foreign
aid mission in Lithuania on Wednesday, another on a list of
regional countries to become ''graduates'' of the assistance
program.
</P>
<P>
   Missions in seven others have already closed down, including
Latvia and Estonia, both Baltic neighbors of Lithuania, said Donald
Pressley, assistant administrator of the Agency for International
Development.
</P>
<P>
   The mission in Poland will be closed in July. That will be the
last of eight formerly communist countries in the area to be
deleted from the aid recipient list.
</P>
<P>
   Pressley will take part in a ceremony Wednesday formally
shutting the AID office in Vilnius, the Lithuanian capital.
</P>
<P>
   Over 10 years, Lithuania has received about $80 million in U.S.
assistance. Included have been programs to support civil society
and the promotion of a market economy.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Baltics surged into transition process right from
beginning,'' said Pressley.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was something that they welcomed, even though there were
painful results in terms of societal implications but they saw
there were much larger rewards.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those countries that have taken the difficult reform steps are
now the ones that are doing the best,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
