<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Summary of Supreme Court Actions  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   The Supreme Court took these actions Tuesday:
<TEXT>
<P>
   --Expanded its review of a major clean-air dispute, agreeing to
decide whether anti-pollution regulations must take into account
compliance costs as well as health effects. Environmentalists
criticized the action, while industry representatives praised the
justices for adding the cost issue to a Clean Air Act case they
agreed to review last week.
</P>
<P>
   --Ruled unanimously in a Missouri case that companies that
provide services to a business during its bankruptcy proceedings
cannot try to collect unpaid fees from collateral held by another
creditor. The court said only bankruptcy trustees can recover costs
in such a manner.
</P>
<P>
   --Made it easier for governments to collect back taxes from
bankrupt debtors. Ruling unanimously in an Illinois dispute over
state sales taxes owed on a corporate jet, the court said that if a
tax law puts the burden of proof on the taxpayer instead of the
government, that burden remains the same if the tax dispute becomes
part of a bankruptcy case.
</P>
<P>
   --Agreed to clarify whether courts must defer to U.S. Customs
Service rulings on whether import duties should be paid on certain
products. The government says a lower court erred in saying it need
not defer to Customs findings in a dispute over whether an Ohio
company must pay a duty to import loose-leaf daily planners.
</P>
<P>
   --Agreed to referee a dispute between Virginia and Maryland over
whether Virginia can extend a drinking-water intake pipe halfway
across the Potomac River. Maryland owns the entire Potomac River
where it touches both states, but Virginia long has had the right
to use water from the river.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
