<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Newly battle-scarred Lazio is GOP choice to face Clinton  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- His fresh face marred by a fat lip, Rep.
Rick Lazio was to be nominated Tuesday by his Republican Party's
leadership to battle Hillary Rodham Clinton in New York's
high-profile U.S. Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to take this block by block, house by house,''
Lazio told reporters before a breakfast with a small group of
supporters at a Buffalo restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   For Lazio, 42, it marked the culmination of a dream that seemed
dashed just nine months ago when Gov. George Pataki convinced the
congressman to suspend his fledgling Senate campaign in favor of
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's expected run.
</P>
<P>
   The dream was reborn on May 19 when the New York City mayor
announced he was leaving the Senate race because of prostate
cancer. Pataki and other Republican leaders quickly rallied around
the little-known Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since, Republicans have been dismissing the first lady's
star power advantage, maintaining the race would now become one of
issues and experience, rather than celebrity. They also took note
of the New York City's mayor's testiness and seeming lack of
enthusiasm for the Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rudy was certainly better known than Rick is, initially, but
with that were a lot of pluses and minuses,'' state GOP Chairman
William Powers said before Tuesday's convention began. ''Rick seems
to have all of the pluses and not as many of the minuses.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It seemed that the mayor wanted the office but he didn't
really want to campaign for it,'' said Larry Staub, vice chairman
of the Monroe County GOP.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio arrived in Buffalo as a wounded warrior. He tripped Monday
during a Memorial Day parade on Long Island, splitting his lip. It
required eight stitches to close.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, expecting a tough race against Clinton and seeking
to disspell any notion the stumble could be a metaphor for the GOP
campaign, made light of the wound.
</P>
<P>
   ''It'll be the first of a few,'' Powers remarked.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the state Democratic convention in Albany where
more than 10,000 people gathered in a cavernous sports arena two
weeks ago to witness the first lady's nomination, with President
Clinton at her side, the more than 400 Republican delegates
gathered in the ballroom of a Buffalo hotel. Powers said he
expected about 2,000 people in all.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani was not among the guests, chosing to stay away rather
than upstage his newly minted replacement. The two did campaign
together Monday at a parade in Queens, their first joint appearance
since Lazio jumped into the race.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going to do everything I can to help him get elected,''
the New York City mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Buffalo hotel, more than 200 state prison guards
displayed their unhappiness with going more than a year without a
new contract with the Pataki administration by raining on Lazio's
parade.
</P>
<P>
   ''Lazio, we vote!'' the protesters chanted. On May 18,
negotitators for the union and the state reached a tentative
agreement on a new four-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   Independent polls, even before the Giuliani withdrawal, have
shown Clinton hovering in the mid-40 percentage range, giving
Republicans hope that Lazio can copy the giant-killer role played
by Pataki in 1994 when, as a little-known state senator, he toppled
three-term Democratic Gov. Mario Cuomo.
</P>
<P>
   Like Pataki, Lazio is from the suburbs surrounding New York City
and is considered a moderate Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ''New Yorkers like the underdog,'' Powers said.
</P>
<P>
   Since entering the race, Lazio has been stressing his New York
roots, a none-too-subtle reminder that Clinton only moved into the
state in January. And, he has pointed to his record as a four-term
congressman who helped overhaul the nation's public housing system,
worked to protect the environment and voted to raise the minimum
wage.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton camp, on the other hand, has been portraying Lazio
as a conservative out of step with mainstream New Yorkers. Clinton
aides have repeatedly pointed to Lazio's support for eight out of
10 proposals from former House Speaker Newt Gingrich's ''Contract
with America.'' She has also taken her rival to task for saying
he's a supporter of abortion rights, noting he has regularly voted
to cut federal Medicaid funding for poor women's abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Clinton and Giuliani, Lazio has also come out in favor of
banning the late-term abortion procedure that critics called
''partial-birth abortion.'' That has cleared the way for him to
pick up the endorsement of the state's Conservative Party. No
Republican has won statewide office in New York since 1974 without
Conservative Party backing.
</P>
<P>
   Emulating Bill Clinton's successful 1992 presidential campaign
and Sen. John McCain's failed run for the White House this year,
Lazio was to leave the convention Tuesday night for a three-day bus
trip across the state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-30-00 1357 </TRAILER>
