<HEADLINE> Bausch &AMP; Lomb loses out as CIBA Vision buy Wesley Jessen for $785 million </HEADLINE>
By BEN DOBBIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- Bausch &AMP; Lomb Inc. abandoned its
10-week-long pursuit of Wesley Jessen VisionCare Inc. after the Des
Plaines, Ill.-based cosmetic contact lens maker revealed Tuesday it
had accepted a $785 million buyout offer from CIBA Vision.
</P>
<P>
   The deal with Atlanta-based CIBA, the eye-care unit of Swiss
pharmaceutical giant Novartis, tops a sweetened but hostile bid
valued at about $725 million that Bausch &AMP; Lomb Inc. made for
Wesley Jessen on May 8.
</P>
<P>
   Wesley Jessen shares jumped nearly 14 percent. Novartis said the
combined CIBA-Wesley Jessen would be the world's second largest
contact lens company, with pro forma sales last year of $1.4
billion and a combined work force of 8,900.
</P>
<P>
   Approving of CIBA's cash offer of $38.50 a share in cash, Wesley
Jessen broke off its proposed merger with Ocular Sciences Inc. and
paid the contact lens company in South San Francisco a $25 million
termination fee.
</P>
<P>
   Bausch &AMP; Lomb's ''best and final'' bid of $35.55 a share in cash
had been set to expire Wednesday. But the eye-care company, which
has strength in premium disposable lenses, cited the definitive
agreement between Wesley Jessen and CIBA in withdrawing its offer.
</P>
<P>
   Chief executive William Carpenter said ''we considered the
acquisition of Wesley Jessen to be strategically appropriate ...
but only at a price that is attractive to the Bausch &AMP; Lomb
shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   Wesley Jessen controls about two-thirds of the highly profitable
cosmetic color-lens market. It had $311.7 million in sales last
year.
</P>
<P>
   The CIBA offer represents a premium of about 17 percent over the
closing price of Wesley Jessen's shares Friday. It is a 55 percent
premium over the closing price March 22, the last trading day
before Bausch &AMP; Lomb announced its original, $34 a share bid for
Wesley Jessen.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was expected to be completed in the third quarter. It
would be subject to 51 percent of the Wesley Jessen shares being
tendered as well as other regulatory and customary conditions,
Novartis said.
</P>
<P>
   In trading on the Nasdaq Stock Market, Wesley Jessen rose 13.75
percent, or $4.187, to $37.375 a share. Shares of Bausch &AMP; Lomb
fell 31.3 cents to $71.625 on the New York Stock Exchange, where
shares of Novartis fell 6.25 cents to $37.
</P>
<P>
   Wesley Jessen has postponed indefinitely its annual shareholder
meeting, which was scheduled for June 23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-30-00 1404 </TRAILER>
