<HEADLINE> Dow Up 128; Nasdaq Up 144  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks moved sharply higher today as investors
returned from a three-day weekend ready to look for bargains.
Technology and telecom stocks led the gains.
</P>
<P>
   In afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 128.85 at 10,428.09.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Nasdaq composite
index was up 144.90 at 3,350.01, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was up 24.64 at 1,402.66.
</P>
<P>
   ''Investors are in a buying mood,'' said Alan Skrainka, chief
market strategist at Edward Jones of St. Louis. ''At the close of
trading last week, the Nasdaq was 37 percent off its record high,
and many investors believe that there are bargains to be found.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, volume was light, suggesting that investors remain wary.
</P>
<P>
   The telecommunications sector received a lift from the news that
France Telecom is buying Britain's Orange from Vodafone Air Touch
PLC for about $37.6 billion in cash and stock.
</P>
<P>
   France Telecom shares rose $7 to $138 on the New York Stock
Exchange, and Vodafone Air Touch rose $4.063 to $46.063.
</P>
<P>
   The deal raised speculation that more global mergers will follow
in the telecom industry. Alcatel rose $5.625 to $54.625.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of high-tech industry leaders also rose. Sun Microsystems
rose $3.438 to $76.688 and Cisco Systems rose $3 to $57.938.
</P>
<P>
   Intel rose $5.063 to $122.625 after Lehman Brothers analyst Dan
Niles, who joined the firm from BancBoston Robertson Stephens,
launched coverage with a ''buy'' rating and called Intel one of his
favorite stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Many high-profile technology stocks have been under pressure in
recent weeks as investors have wondered whether their future
earnings will justify their relatively high share prices. Most
analysts expect rising interest rates to eventually take a toll on
corporate earnings as it become more expensive to borrow money to
finance growth.
</P>
<P>
   Technology companies could be hurt if their old-economy clients
curb spending on technology while they weather rising interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Lee edged up $0.063 to $18.625 after the company announced
plans to tighten its focus by selling all or part of several
businesses including Coach leather goods and Champion athletic
wear.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Lee officials said the restructuring will enhance longtime
earnings but could slow growth over the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks rose despite an economic report that suggested six rate
increases by the Federal Reserve in the past year have not yet
sapped consumer sentiment. Consumer confidence jumped sharply in
May, approaching the all-time high it reached in January, the
Conference Board said.
</P>
<P>
   On a weaker day, the robust report could have prompted a
selloff. Today, eager investors were choosing to gloss over the
consumer confidence report and look ahead to a pair of reports due
out later this week.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a reflection of Wall Street's manic depressive state,''
Skrainka said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the National Association of Purchasing Management
will issue a report on activity in the industrial economy during
May. And on Friday, the Labor Department will issue its May
employment report.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by an 8-to-5 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to a modest 533.87
million shares, just slightly ahead of Friday's sluggish pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index rose 9.79 to 467.16.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
