<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 14:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court To Decide Potomac River Fight  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD CARELLI
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today agreed to referee a
dispute between Virginia and Maryland over the Potomac River.
</P>
<P>
   The justices allowed Virginia to sue Maryland in the nation's
highest court by invoking their ''original jurisdiction'' -- the
authority to resolve certain conflicts between states even before
any other court considers them.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is Virginia's right to extend a drinking-water intake
pipe halfway across the river.
</P>
<P>
   Under a 1632 land grant, Maryland owns the entire Potomac River
where it touches both states. Virginia's boundary ends at the
river's low water mark on the Virginia side.
</P>
<P>
   For at least 133 years, however, Virginia has had the right to
use Potomac River water. Today, some 1.2 million Virginians depend
on the Potomac for their drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   The present water intake pipe, according to Virginia officials,
is situated too close to land to avoid sediment and other
pollutants. Officials say that by extending the pipe, which would
be submerged below the river's surface to avoid interference with
navigation, the state would save millions in water treatment costs.
</P>
<P>
   The Fairfax County (Va.) Water Authority applied for a
construction permit in 1996 but Maryland officials have not yet
issued one. Maryland officials have cited environmental concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia's appeal to the Supreme Court challenged Maryland's
authority to require a permit, and accused Maryland officials of
wrongly requiring Virginia to demonstrate a ''need'' for the
construction.
</P>
<P>
   ''Based on Maryland's past performance, there is every prospect
that, in large part for political reasons, Maryland will continue
to delay for years and ultimately deny Virginia its permit, and
that the Maryland courts will uphold that determination,'' the
Virginia appeal said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no alternative forum that can provide a fair and
prompt resolution of this case,'' it added.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland officials urged the justices to reject the appeal. They
noted that the dispute is before a Maryland administrative judge
who will issue an opinion by the end of May.
</P>
<P>
   The Maryland officials also contended that the dispute is not
really between two states, but instead is between Maryland and
Fairfax County. ''No controversy exists between Maryland and
Virginia other than the ... claims ... by one of (Virginia's)
political subdivisions,'' they said.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland Gov. Parris Glendening said last week he plans to sign
a bill that would allow Virginia to extend the intake pipe once the
Maryland Department of the Environment approves the project.
</P>
<P>
   But Virginia officials contend Maryland does not have the
authority to reject the intake pipe's construction.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Byrnie, a spokeswoman for Glendening, reacted to
today's action by stating: ''Maryland has serious concerns about
the environmental impact of a new water intake pipe. The governor
is confident that the Supreme Court will recognize that Maryland
has taken reasonable and appropriate action to address those
concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Attorney General Mark Earley said, ''Our ability to
provide clean water to our citizens, free from obstruction by
Maryland, is at the heart of this case. We ... are optimistic the
court will uphold our right to an adequate supply of drinking water
for the health and safety.''
</P>
<P>
   The case is Virginia vs. Maryland, 129 Original.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-30-00 1438 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
