<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 15:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NU, ConEd negotiate consumer benefits of merger  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) -- Negotiators are trying to put more
consumer benefits into the proposed merger of Northeast Utilities
and Consolidated Edison Inc. so the deal will look sweeter to
Connecticut regulators.
</P>
<P>
   At issue are rate cuts, job protections, corporate donations,
land preservation and other benefits for customers in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations have been going on for a month. The utilities faced
a Tuesday deadline to file a settlement, ask for regulatory
proceedings to resume or ask to continue talks.
</P>
<P>
   Northeast Utilities said it would notify the Department of
Public Utility Control of its next step Wednesday. The DPUC can
reject or alter any settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ''We haven't closed the door yet. We wish that something would
be worked out,'' NU spokesman Frank Poirot said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The companies started negotiating after consumer advocates and
even one DPUC commissioner berated the utilities for offering
little or nothing to Connecticut consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The $7.5 billion merger would create the country's largest
electric and gas distribution company, with more than 6.4 million
customers in New York and New England.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Glenn Arthur urged ConEd and NU to offer more
benefits to customers, saying the original proposal was ''not a
dead ringer for approval.''
</P>
<P>
   The original proposal did not include rate cuts for Connecticut
consumers until 2006, Attorney General Richard Blumenthal
complained.
</P>
<P>
   NU responded that its customers already enjoy a 10 percent rate
cut under the state's electric deregulation law. The companies
pledged more savings once the combined companies found ways to
streamline operations.
</P>
<P>
   Job losses are expected, but the companies said they would try
to reduce their combined work force through attrition and
retraining.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed merger, the headquarters of the combined
company would be in New York. Berlin would remain the headquarters
of Connecticut Light &AMP; Power Co., and NU's other subsidiary
utilities in New Hampshire and Massachusetts would keep their
current headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates seek stronger job protections and want to
keep more jobs in Connecticut. Environmental groups are concerned
that the merger would lead to the sale of thousands of acres owned
by NU.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-30-00 1538 </TRAILER>
