<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Modern-day witches charmed by Harry Potter  </HEADLINE>
By DEEPTI HAJELA
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- He's a charmer, that Harry Potter. The
adolescent hero of J.K. Rowling's series rides a broom, owns an
Invisibility Cloak and a magic wand and has cast a spell over young
readers the world over.
</P>
<P>
   He's got modern-day witches enchanted, too.
</P>
<P>
   ''For once, the witches aren't ugly old hags,'' said Michael
Darnell, a 39-year-old computer programmer from Winnipeg, Canada,
who has been a practicing witch for 25 years. ''For once they're
the protagonists rather than the villains.''
</P>
<P>
   Darnell is one of the thousands of North American adherents of
Wicca, a faith linked to witchcraft. In the United States, Wicca
was recognized in a 1986 federal appeals court decision giving it
tax exempt status. No one knows how many people practice Wicca, but
estimates run anywhere from 300,000 to more than 1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Its followers describe Wicca as a nature-based belief system
that existed in Europe before Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   But witchcraft has always had a darker image in popular culture,
often linked to devil worship and decried by some Christians as an
affront to God.
</P>
<P>
   From Shakespeare to Salem, witches have usually been portrayed
as evil, curse-casting troublemakers. Not in Harry's case. He and
his friends go to school to learn witchcraft and have all kinds of
magical adventures along the way. In his world, the non-witches are
the weird ones.
</P>
<P>
   That's a welcome change for witchcraft practitioners.
</P>
<P>
   ''If somebody wants to write about us as being fun, interesting,
magical people, we don't mind that at all,'' said Jane Raeburn, 35,
a writer in Wells, Maine, who has been practicing Wicca for 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   ''Considering what the image was 400 years ago in Salem, it's
quite a switch,'' said Michael Thorn, 44, of Mastic, N.Y., who has
been a witch since 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Salem, Mass., was the setting for a number of infamous witch
trials in the spring and summer of 1692. Nineteen men and women
were convicted of being witches and hanged, and numerous others
were harassed or jailed. Those suspected of witchcraft were accused
of making ghostly visits to torture people and causing livestock
deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The Potter books -- the fourth volume is scheduled for release on
July 8 -- don't actually deal with the philosophical precepts of
Wicca or any specific religious tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Instead Harry and company fight the good fight against the
forces of evil aided by the stereotypical pop culture notions of
witchery -- flying brooms, magical instruments, spells.
</P>
<P>
   That in itself has been enough to concern some Christian
parents. Last year, the series topped the list of books that
parents or certain groups tried to have taken off shelves,
according to the American Library Association. The books were
removed in some schools after parents raised concerns that the
series was promoting witchcraft.
</P>
<P>
   Modern-day witches find that laughable.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're fairy tales, they're not religious discourses,'' Thorn
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''They don't have anything to do with Wicca,'' said Patricia
Allgeier, 57, a witch in Springfield, Mo. ''It's this generation's
version of 'The Wizard of Oz.'''
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say witches don't have any concerns about the
books. Anything that promotes stereotypes, even positively, can
make it more difficult for Wiccans to deal with non-Wiccans.
</P>
<P>
   ''It portrays witches in positive ways ... but it does not
portray my religious beliefs,'' said Chad Anctil, of the Witches'
League for Public Awareness.
</P>
<P>
   A self-avowed big admirer of the Harry Potter books, Anctil
loves them for their well-written, entertaining stories. But ''it
is difficult for the religion to be taken seriously when books like
this portray it as magic,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What makes witches like the books are the same things that
appeal to non-witches: Author Rowling has created an engaging
series that explores the difficulties of growing up and has kids
dealing with issues of right and wrong -- and standing up for what
they believe.
</P>
<P>
   ''What you're talking about are the choices people make,'' said
Christina Aubin, parenting coordinator for the Clearwater,
Fla.-based Web site The Witches' Voice.
</P>
<P>
   Her 10-year-old daughter is a huge Harry Potter fan.
</P>
<P>
   ''It teaches her to think for herself,'' Aubin said. ''I don't
think that's a bad idea.''
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, any parent, witch or not, can't help but be
excited about books their children can't wait to read. That's the
case for Michael Darnell's 9-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   ''It really set fire to his reading,'' Darnell said. ''We'd
tried to get him toward thicker books, but he wanted to only read
picture books.''
</P>
<P>
   So there is a kind of magic involved with Harry Potter, Darnell
admits.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is what these books do, they become reading for
entertainment,'' he said. ''That's a spell. ... the spell of
reading, that's a good one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-30-00 1553 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000530.0071 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Justice May Block Gas Pump Deal  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department intends to file suit to
block a deal it said would eliminate competition in the sale of
pumps used in 90 percent of U.S. gas stations to transfer gasoline
from underground tanks to surface dispensers.
</P>
<P>
   The department said Tuesday its planned civil antitrust suit
would block a proposed joint venture between Franklin Electric Co.
Inc. and United Dominion Industries Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would combine the assets of Franklin Electric's
subsidiary FE Petro and the petroleum related assets of United
Dominion's subsidiary, The Marley Co.
</P>
<P>
   The two subsidiaries now compete with each other and are the
only two companies that produce and sell submersible turbine pumps
in this country. The government said the Marley's ''Red Jacket''
turbine pumps have 60 percent of the market, compared to 40 percent
for FE Petro's pumps.
</P>
<P>
   The joint venture would be 75 percent owned by Franklin Electric
and 25 percent by Marley. It would eliminate head-to-head
competition between the two companies, the government said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This proposed joint venture would eliminate competition and
create a monopoly in the sale of submersible turbine pumps in the
United States, resulting in higher prices, less innovation and
lower quality service for customers,'' Assistant Attorney General
Joel I. Klein said. ''This is the classic kind of competitive
problem that the antitrust laws were intended to prevent.'''
</P>
<P>
   Headquartered in Bluffton, Ind., Franklin Electric reported 1999
sales of $293.2 million. It's FE Petro subsidiary produces
submersible turbine pumps at a plant in McFarland, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   A wholly owned subsidiary of United Dominion Industries Limited,
United Dominion is headquartered in Charlotte, N.C. United Dominion
Industries Limited is a Canadian corporation with sales of $2.15
billion in 1999. Its Marley subsidiary produces the pumps at a
plant in Davenport, Iowa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-30-00 1554 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000530.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> VA Seeks Better Patient Safety  </HEADLINE>
By LAURAN NEERGAARD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a groundbreaking program, the nation's
veterans hospitals hired NASA on Tuesday to do for medical safety
what it does for airline safety: Set up a system where errors can
be reported without fear of penalty and use the information to make
everyone safer.
</P>
<P>
   A NASA-run program that lets pilots report near misses is widely
considered so successful at improving aviation safety that the
Department of Veterans Affairs wants a similar program to combat
medical mistakes. It would let doctors and nurses report problems
that, if fixed, could improve care in the VA's 172 hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   A stunning report by the prestigious Institute of Medicine last
year concluded that medical mistakes kill 44,000 to 98,000
hospitalized Americans a year.
</P>
<P>
   One of the institute's biggest recommendations was to copy the
aviation industry to improve safety. In a move health experts have
called innovative, the VA has worked for months to do just that.
Now the question is whether the three-year, $8.2 million experiment
will work.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will be an experiment followed with great interest,'' said
Dr. Nancy Dickey, past president of the American Medical
Association, who leads that group's own safety-improvement work.
</P>
<P>
   Many medical errors are preventable if hospitals would analyze
patterns of problems and install safety nets. Health workers often
do not disclose errors, however, for fear they could be sued or
fired.
</P>
<P>
   The VA already requires employees to report certain serious
errors. The new voluntary, anonymous program aims to uncover more
problems, especially the near miss that didn't hurt a patient but
might the next time.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you don't know about it, you can't fix it,'' explained Dr.
Thomas Garthwaite, the VA's acting undersecretary for health.
</P>
<P>
   Under the program, any VA health worker can report medical
mistakes they make or witness. Just as in the pilots' program, no
doctor or nurse would be held personally at fault. After
questioning the health worker for more details, NASA will strip
identifying information from its database so bosses cannot tell who
reported what.
</P>
<P>
   Then NASA-hired medical experts will analyze how an error
happened and seek protections to prevent it from happening again.
</P>
<P>
   ''This kind of reporting is absolutely essential,'' said Dr.
John Eisenberg, who heads President Clinton's health quality task
force. ''If to err is human, it seems (that) to do nothing about
our medical errors is inhumane.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to install safeguards against mistakes instead of
laying blame, said Dr. James Bagian, the astronaut and physician
credited with installing escape hatches to make the space shuttle
safer and who now is trying to make the VA health system safer.
</P>
<P>
   An example: A nurse hands out a wrong pill, because its name and
package closely resemble a drug next to it on a hospital's pharmacy
shelf. The patient isn't seriously harmed, and thus no one else
notices the mistake; should the nurse risk a reprimand by revealing
her gaffe?
</P>
<P>
   With the new system, she wouldn't have to. Reporting the mistake
into the confidential database could prompt NASA to highlight
confusing medications so VA hospitals could prevent future mix-ups.
</P>
<P>
   NASA's Aviation Safety Reporting System, run for the Federal
Aviation Administration, receives 35,000 reports a year of close
calls or aviation mistakes. A team of retired pilots and air
traffic controllers, plus a computerized program that automatically
searches for patterns of errors, hunts solutions to make future
flights safer. The program sends out about 20 safety alerts a month
to the FAA or other industry groups highlighting potential
problems.
</P>
<P>
   In 24 years, the system has never breached a pilot's
confidentiality, said system director Linda Connell. That
confidentiality will be key to health workers trusting the new
program enough to report problems, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bagian said NASA, which formally agreed Tuesday to run the VA
program, should receive the first error reports from VA employees
by January.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-30-00 1555 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000530.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> VA Uses NASA Model To Boost Safety  </HEADLINE>
By LAURAN NEERGAARD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a groundbreaking program, the nation's
veterans hospitals hired NASA on Tuesday to do for medical safety
what it does for airline safety: Set up a system where errors can
