<HEADLINE> Palestinians Reunite at Border  </HEADLINE>
By SUSAN SEVAREID
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOHEIRA, Lebanon (AP) -- Palestinian relatives who'd never met
stretched hands through swirls of barbed wire at the Lebanon-Israel
border Tuesday, making introductions and asking whatever happened
to loved ones in each other's land.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wonder, my dearest, where is Abu Khaled?'' Najah Fahd, a
resident of the Israeli town of Tamra, asked cousins on the
Lebanese side.
</P>
<P>
   She gripped the fence between them and broke into tears. Soon
others gathered and, at the urging of an Israeli soldier, the woman
was escorted back without an answer.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanon is home to 350,000 Palestinian refugees, forced from
their homes by the creation of Israel in 1948 and the 1967 Middle
East war. And of Israel's 6 million people, about 1 million are
Arabs who continued to live in the former Palestine after the
creation of the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians on each side have been separated for years by
the Israeli occupied zone in southern Lebanon. With Israel's troop
withdrawal from the border zone last week, reunions between
relatives on both sides of the fence have become possible.
</P>
<P>
   From refugee camps and towns across Lebanon, about 100
Palestinians -- infants and elderly -- made their way 300 yards up a
rocky hill and steep slope Tuesday to squeeze onto the narrow
gravel strip along the barbed wire fence that divides Lebanon and
Israel. Those who came hung on to the border fence for balance as
they squeezed past others on the border ledge. No Lebanese
authorities were present.
</P>
<P>
   On the Israeli side, three Israeli soldiers made halfhearted
efforts to keep about 175 relatives behind coils of barbed wire 10
feet back from the fence. But they tolerated approaches as long as
reunions were brief and too many people didn't cluster at once.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is your brother's daughter. Her name is Umm Khalid,'' a
woman on the Lebanese side said as two women -- an aunt and a niece
from opposite sides of the fence -- reached out to shake hands for
the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the Israeli withdrawal from southern Lebanon, a
peaceful border that relatives could pass through for visits
remains a long way off. And many on the Lebanese side complain that
current Israeli-Palestinian peace talks are unlikely to include
their return to their homeland. For now, word-of-mouth arrangements
are being made for fence reunions between people hoping to fill in
the 52-year gap in family histories.
</P>
<P>
   On the Israeli side of the fence Tuesday, Ali Suweidan stood and
spoke to a young man across the way in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am their uncle -- tell your neighbors to come Saturday
because I am coming back,'' he said. ''Give them my regards and
tell them to come back Saturday,'' he said again as an Israeli
soldier shooed him back from the fence.
</P>
<P>
   Suweidan comes from what used to be the town of Basa, six miles
inside Israel. The town -- whose Arab residents fled in 1948 -- no
longer exists, and the industrial zone of the Israeli community of
Shlomi is now located on the site. Suweidan lives elsewhere inside
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Zuhair Merei, 22, who lives in Zrariyeh village near the
southern Lebanese town of Tyre, pointed through the fence to two
teen-age girls on the Israeli side. The girls, whose families also
come from Basa, sucked yellow popsicles. They smiled back and
waved.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those are my cousins,'' Merei said. Then he blushed and asked
them again who is Amal and who is Sahar.
</P>
<P>
   Mohammed Sabah, 72, rested on a cooler, holding his cane and
sipping a cup of Arabic coffee from a pot passed through from the
fence.
</P>
<P>
   Sabah, originally from Amka village in the Galilee in Israel,
now lives in the southern Lebanese port city of Sidon. He said
relatives carried him up the hill to the border fence.
</P>
<P>
   There, he visited briefly with some of his wife's family on the
Israeli side and looked into the land he left 52 years ago as a
refugee.
</P>
<P>
   ''Even if this is the last day of my life, I'll accept only
Palestine as my homeland,'' Sabah said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-30-00 1643 </TRAILER>
