<DOCNO> APW20000530.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Won't Deploy Army in South  </HEADLINE>
By SUSAN SEVAREID
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAQOURA, Lebanon (AP) -- Israel's army blew up more outposts and
leftover material Tuesday in its fallback to the Lebanese-Israeli
border as U.N. teams worked on restoring the frontier to lines
prior to the 1978 Israeli invasion.
</P>
<P>
   Several explosions echoed in spots just inside Lebanon, and a
cloud of white dust shot into the sky in the early afternoon. The
Israeli army spokesman in Jerusalem said one explosion was part of
the deployment to the border, while Israeli military sources said
two blasts near the army's former Tziporen position just inside
Lebanon were part of the disposal of concrete blocks and other
leftovers.
</P>
<P>
   The explosions were all part of an Israeli move to complete its
pullback from an occupied zone it set up in southern Lebanon in
1985.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli army finished withdrawing last Wednesday, and since
then it has been moving some border outposts because the positions
were inside Lebanese territory. The exact location of the pre-1978
border became muddled during the long Israeli occupation.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. verification of the Israeli withdrawal is a requirement for
the deployment of a 4,500-member U.N. peacekeeping force in the
former occupied zone all the way to the international border.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. envoy Terje Roed Larsen, who is arranging for the
deployment of the peacekeepers, on Tuesday said the Israelis have
vacated the interior of southern Lebanon and are working
''intensively'' to move positions out of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ''Over the years, Israel has built a considerable amount of
security-related infrastructure on the Lebanese side of the border.
... The United Nations has made very clear that no Israeli presence
can remain in Lebanon,'' Larsen said in a statement Monday.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, he traveled to the border area to follow up the work
of U.N. teams marking the international frontier. U.N.
cartographers led by a de-mining unit and accompanied by soldiers
carrying paints and brushes have been laboring with details of maps
and geography to redraw the international border.
</P>
<P>
   Larsen said Monday that ''barring unexpected complications'' he
hoped the marking of the border would be completed in the ''next
few days.'' On Tuesday, Israel TV reported that Larsen and Danny
Yatom, a security adviser to Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak,
agreed in a meeting on the placement of the entire border. Barak
spokesman Gadi Baltiansky refused to comment and a spokesman for
U.N. troops in Lebanon said he did not know what went on in the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanon, meanwhile, said it is not yet time to send its army to
areas vacated by Israel. The U.N. must first verify the Israeli
withdrawal and deploy peacekeepers in its area of operations, Prime
Minister Salim Hoss said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Muslim guerrillas moved into the zone after Israel's pullout,
and Christians in the south say they fear for their safety. There
have been reports of looting and break-ins in areas inhabited by
Christians, some of whom allied with Israel during its long
involvement in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of policemen have been sent to the former
Israeli-occupied areas but the government has refused to send the
army, saying its military will not act as a border guard for
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the border, Israelis have been worrying
about their security situation now that the Israeli army is no
longer serving as a buffer in Lebanon. The town of Metulla has
begun distributing M-16s and automatic rifles to residents worried
about possible guerrilla attacks, since the border now runs only
yards from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are distributing weapons because people want to feel more
secure,'' said the head of security in Metulla, Amir Shoshani. Only
residents who have served in the army and have licenses are
permitted to receive the automatic weapons, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday in Israel, U.S. Ambassador to Israel Martin Indyk
said the United States is releasing $50 million in military aid to
let Israel beef up security along the tense border with Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   The sum does not constitute additional aid to Israel, said Larry
Schwartz, spokesman for the U.S. Embassy in Tel Aviv. The decision
means Israel will be able to spend the money locally instead of in
the United States, Schwartz said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-30-00 1702 </TRAILER>
