<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Some in White House Gone, Packing  </HEADLINE>
By ANNE GEARAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- For a few hundred White House aides, many of
whom have worked for Bill Clinton since 1991 or 1992, this is like
senior year: time to move on.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the president's advisers and retainers are taking an
early slide while others work on their resumes.
</P>
<P>
   ''I basically grew up there,'' said David Leavy, who took a job
with Clinton one day out of college in 1991 and left the White
House as the senior foreign policy spokesman this year at age 30.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had a really wonderful and once-in-a-lifetime experience,
but a narrow one,'' Leavy said. ''Come Year 8, it was really time
to do something else.''
</P>
<P>
   For him, something else was a big public relations job for the
parent company of the Discovery channel. Doug Sosnik, one of
Clinton's most trusted strategists, also left this year for a
senior management job with the National Basketball Association.
Longtime spokesman Barry Toiv joined a Washington public relations
firm.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best-known of Clinton's top aides, press secretary
Joe Lockhart, has told colleagues he is leaving this fall. There
are loud whispers that senior foreign policy adviser Jim Steinberg
is leaving, along with deputy chief of staff Steve Ricchetti.
</P>
<P>
   Other recognizable faces left long ago -- among them adviser
George Stephanopolous and press secretaries Dee Dee Myers and Mike
McCurry.
</P>
<P>
   Some are secretive about their job searches, others only too
happy to leak word that they're available.
</P>
<P>
   ''With the beginning of the end of the administration, there is
a presumption that people are leaving,'' said one senior staffer
who left last year and spoke anonymously. ''You need to be careful
about actively negotiating while you're still there,'' to avoid
conflicts of interest, but there are few other restrictions, the
former aide said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's trip to Europe this week will be the swan song for at
least two assistants, including the president's personal aide and
card partner, Kris Engskov, who is joining a Seattle venture
capital firm. Press assistant Mark Bernstein is off to Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Many other junior aides will leave this summer for graduate
school or law school, and some will not be replaced. Hardly a week
passes without a goodbye party, which range from catered spreads
and champagne toasts down to pretzels and ginger ale.
</P>
<P>
   But several current and former White House aides said they are
surprised by how many ''lifers'' are still around, and how many
intend to stay to the end.
</P>
<P>
   Chief of staff John Podesta will likely stay on, along with
legislative strategist Joel Johnson, economic adviser Gene
Sperling, national security adviser Sandy Berger and domestic
policy adviser Bruce Reed, White House aides said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Public expectation and public perceptions might be that staff
would be leaving in great numbers in the eighth year, and that has
not turned out to be the case,'' said spokeswoman Jennifer
Palmieri, who intends to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that the further we get into the eighth year, the more
people have realized the responsibilities of these positions are
such that most of the senior people are going to want to and need
to stay until the end,'' Palmieri said.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean they can't start looking for the job they will
take next January, however.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton alluded to the mass job hunt in his remarks last month
at the White House Correspondents' Association dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm working hard on this resume deal,'' Clinton joked. ''I've
been getting a lot of tips on how to write it, mostly from my
staff. They really seem to be up on this stuff.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-30-00 1705 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
