<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sea-Based Missile System Eyed  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BURNS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Pentagon is spending $7 million to study
the feasibility of adding a sea-based element to a national missile
defense system that currently includes only land-based weapons,
officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The study, required by Congress and now more than a month
overdue, comes as President Clinton prepares to decide -- probably
by November -- whether to go ahead with a defense against ballistic
missiles of the type that North Korea is developing.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said the administration
believes the only way to develop a national missile defense by the
target date of 2005 is to exclude sea-based elements, which require
more technical work.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our feeling is that a sea-based system requires more
development and would take more time and possibly cost more money
than a land-based system,'' Bacon said. ''But we are examining
that.'' He said the Pentagon is spending about $7 million ''to look
at the pros and cons of a sea-based system and what it would
require to make a sea-based system work or to give us a sea-based
element to a land-based system.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacon would not comment directly on a Washington Post report
that the Pentagon has concluded that sea-based national missile
defenses could be built with existing technology and would improve
the proposed land-based system.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right now we are concentrating primarily, in fact almost
exclusively, on developing a land-based system,'' Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   Missile defense has become a topic on the presidential campaign
trail. Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the presumptive Republican
nominee, said in a speech last week that the United States should
develop ''all options'' for missile defense, and that a U.S. system
should be capable of defending allies as well as U.S. territory.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, the expected Democratic nominee, favors
the current administration's approach, which would be a land-based
system that protects all 50 states -- but not allies -- against
long-range missiles.
</P>
<P>
   In a television appearance Sunday, Defense Secretary William
Cohen invited Bush and his national security advisers to the
Pentagon for briefings on the nation's nuclear arsenal and missile
defense plan.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said that Bush's proposal for building a larger missile
defense than the administration's limited one would force the
Russians and others, including China, to increase their own
offensive nuclear arsenals.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Tuesday whether the Bush campaign had responded to Cohen's
invitation, Bacon said, ''The only response we've seen is in the
press, and that was, they said they didn't need such a briefing. So
the secretary considers the issue finished in that they have
rejected the invitation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-30-00 1710 </TRAILER>
