<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Beheaded in Saudi Arabia  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) -- Saudi Arabia beheaded two drug
traffickers and an armed robber on Tuesday, bringing to 49 the
number of people executed in the kingdom this year, the Interior
Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
   Zainallah Khan Argon Khan, a Pakistani, was found guilty of
smuggling an undisclosed quantity of heroin into the Middle Eastern
country. He was beheaded in the capital, Riyadh, a ministry
statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Haji Staro Yousef, a Nigerian, was convicted of smuggling
cocaine into the kingdom, and was beheaded in the Red Sea port city
of Jiddah.
</P>
<P>
   Also in Jiddah, Filipino Manuel Brona was executed after being
found guilty of attempted murder, the statement said. He and an
accomplice, Ronilio Braido, lured a Saudi man to a deserted area,
where Brona stabbed him repeatedly while Braido held him down. The
man escaped and was rescued by passers-by, while his assailants
stole his car and fled, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
   Braido was sentenced to an undisclosed number of lashings and an
unspecified jail term.
</P>
<P>
   At least 99 people were executed in Saudi Arabia in 1999.
Punishments in the Arab country follow a strict interpretation of
Islamic law, entailing execution for murder, rape, sodomy, drug
trafficking and armed robbery. Executions are carried out with a
sword in a public square.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-30-00 1715 </TRAILER>
