<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Weighing Sanctions Against Peru  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE GEDDA
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Troubled by Peru's authoritarian turn, the
Clinton administration is expected to loosen official ties with
that country but will withhold final decisions until after a
meeting with other countries in the region, a State Department
official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the administration backpedaled from an official
statement Sunday in which the victory of Peruvian President Alberto
Fujimori was described as ''invalid.''
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman Philip Reeker limited himself to an
expression of deep regret that Peru decided to proceed with the
election despite findings by an Organization of American States
observer mission that conditions did not exist for a fair
democratic contest.
</P>
<P>
   He said the United States is awaiting a Wednesday meeting of the
OAS permanent council before deciding on future steps.
</P>
<P>
   As for unilateral U.S. action, officials said the administration
is reviewing its policies toward Peru in international lending
organizations. Bilateral aid programs, both military and
non-military, also are being examined, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The official acknowledged that an across-the-board aid cut is
not being considered because of the impact that would have on
Peru's majority poor population.
</P>
<P>
   ''This money does not go into Fujimori's pocket,'' said the
official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   He added that it would be difficult to cut back on the U.S.
counterdrug program in Peru because that issue is a high
administration priority.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori has been an ally in the drug war. The latest State
Department report on the drug situation worldwide, issued in March,
says Peru ''has made enormous strides toward its goal of
eliminating illegal coca cultivation.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. counterdrug assistance for fiscal year 2000 is estimated at
$48 million. The administration hopes to maintain that level in the
next fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Total outlays for U.S. Agency for International Development
programs for Peru, including child survival and food assistance,
are $120.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   While reluctant to suspend aid programs to Peru, the
administration is worried that failure to take strong action
against Peru could tempt anti-democratic forces elsewhere in the
region to move against constitutional governments.
</P>
<P>
   At Wednesday's special OAS meeting, delegates will hear a report
from Eduardo Stein, who headed the OAS observer mission that left
Peru two days before the vote after failing to win agreement for a
delay in the presidential runoff.
</P>
<P>
   The mission wanted a delay because it was not convinced that
electoral authorities had the technical capacity to ensure an
honest vote count.
</P>
<P>
   Stein was meeting Tuesday afternoon with officials of the OAS
democracy promotion unit.
</P>
<P>
   Under a resolution approved in 1991, the permanent council is to
meet in special session if there is a ''sudden or irregular
interruption'' of democratic processes in member countries.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said OAS delegates may decide on Wednesday to refer
Peru's situation to the regular annual meeting of OAS foreign
ministers, set to begin on Sunday in Windsor, Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   The same 1991 resolution authorizes foreign ministers to ''look
into events collectively and adopt any decisions deemed
appropriate,'' in accordance with the OAS charter and international
law.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: State Department:
www.state.gov/www/regions/wha/index.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-30-00 1717 </TRAILER>
