<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canyoning OKd in Swiss Stream  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERN, Switzerland (AP) -- Adventure sports organizers can resume
canyoning trips in an Alpine stream where 21 people drowned in a
flash flood last summer, Swiss authorities said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   National and local officials turned down a proposal by relatives
of the victims for the whole of the Saxeten brook to be turned into
a memorial park.
</P>
<P>
   ''Bern authorities understand the feelings of the victims'
relatives, but maintain that their project is impracticable,'' the
statement said. However, a small memorial park should be created,
it added.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen tourists, many of them Australian, and three employees
of the Adventure World organizing company died in the July 27
accident in the Central Swiss Alps.
</P>
<P>
   Adventure World shut down earlier this month following the death
of 22-year-old American Matthew Coleman in a bungee jumping
accident. He was killed instantly when he slammed into the ground
after being attached to a cord that was too long.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen of the company's staff and directors are under
investigation for negligent homicide in relation to the two
incidents.
</P>
<P>
   Interlaken-based Alpin Raft, which was not involved in the trip
last July organized by local rival Adventure World, will restart
activities in the Saxeten brook later this week, the Bern canton
(state) government said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   New guidelines to improve safety for canyoning, drawn up in the
wake of last year's accident, are ready for this summer, the Swiss
government says.
</P>
<P>
   Canyoning involves sliding, jumping and rappelling down ravines
and into rivers without a raft.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-30-00 1718 </TRAILER>
