<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> RETRANSMITTING n0916 to correct category code  </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Rick Lazio stood amid a roomful of cheering
supporters at a meet-the-candidate luncheon Tuesday and declared
''we have 150 days, as the world looks at us, to prove who we
are.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate candidate who promised earlier in the day to go
''block by block, house by house'' to earn the support of New
Yorkers could have started with the little dry cleaning store that
shares a storefront with the luncheon site.
</P>
<P>
   ''I haven't heard of him,'' said Suzanna Mancuso, who was
vacuuming the store while the Long Island congressman geared up
next door to accept his party's nomination for the U.S. Senate
later in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Rodney Tooles was equally in the dark about the man who stepped
in 11 days earlier to replace New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
in the race against Hillary Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know who he is,'' Tooles said while chaining his bike
to a parking meter at a bank down the street.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio had the support of passer-by Chris Weinert -- not for who
he is, but for who he isn't.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll vote against Hillary Rodham Clinton,'' Weinert said.
</P>
<P>
   It was a start.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio filled his day, before and after accepting the GOP
nomination, with a handful of campaign stops, where he worked to
spread his message and name among crucial upstate voters.
</P>
<P>
   He started by talking economics over cherry danish with about a
dozen Buffalo-area residents at a Greek restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Relating to a father whose son had moved away after college,
Lazio said he has the same concerns for his own first- and
second-grade girls.
</P>
<P>
   ''I worry about them, whether they'll stay close to me, whether
they'll get a job to be able to stay in the area,'' he said, citing
the need for lower taxes and more well-paying jobs.
</P>
<P>
   To several potential voters yet unfamiliar with Lazio's
politics, his strongest attribute appeared to be his status as a
New York native, a point he stressed often.
</P>
<P>
   ''The main thing is the fact that he's a New Yorker. He wants to
keep a New Yorker in office. So do I,'' said Sam Filippone, who was
among those who had breakfast with Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hillary Clinton was probably all right when she was in
Arkansas,'' Filippone said.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's a good place for her,'' chimed his brother, Robert.
</P>
<P>
   ''But this is New York,'' Sam Filippone finished.
</P>
<P>
   After breakfast, it was on to lunch with the ''Women for
Lazio,'' where he shook hands and traded small talk at the
$25-a-plate luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Nickola hadn't heard much about Lazio before he replaced
Giuliani, but she liked what she saw so far.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's come out swinging,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio made another lunchtime visit to an event sponsored by
another New York congressman, Amo Houghton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
