<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Some towns clash with state over aquifer regulation proposals  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Environmentalists and state officials are
pushing for regulations to clean up the state's drinking water
supplies -- nine years after the Legislature ordered those rules to
be in place.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed regulations, which will be the subject of a public
hearing Friday, would stop industries located on or near aquifers
from using certain chemical procedures.
</P>
<P>
   They would also prohibit companies that use those procedures --
such as dry cleaners, gas stations, automotive repair shops and
chemical manufacturing plants -- from moving or expanding near the
underground drinking water supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses now located near the aquifers wouldn't be shut down,
but they would be subject to frequent inspections and forced to
adopt stricter operating procedures.
</P>
<P>
   About 130 companies would be affected by the regulations, said
Fred Banach, assistant director of water management for the
Department of Environmental Protection.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not about evil people doing evil things,'' said Curt
Johnson, spokesman for the Connecticut Coalition for Pure Water.
''It's about recognizing that chemical spills happen and accidents
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said 54 public water wells that supplied about 300,000
people with drinking water have been chemically contaminated during
the past two decades. Six of the wells are still closed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   DEP officials say they expect the regulations to go on the books
by the end of the year. If they do, the rules will come nearly 10
years late.
</P>
<P>
   The General Assembly voted in 1989 to pass the Aquifer
Protection Act, aimed at preventing toxic waste from polluting
public drinking supplies that serve at least 1,000 people. Under
the law, those regulations were to take place in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   But devising a list of regulations that the DEP, businesses and
towns could live with took longer than expected, Banach said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had to take a major step back three years ago and come up
with a far more streamlined version of regulations,'' he said.
''We're not satisfied with the pace of getting everything done, but
there were a number of issues that had to be dealt with.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean the current proposals won't ensure the safety
of Connecticut's drinking water, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some towns that are home to many aquifers and rely
heavily on an industrial tax base say the new regulations are too
harsh.
</P>
<P>
   Southington Town Manager John Weichsel said the prohibitions
will prevent many businesses from moving to the town's ''enterprise
zones'' -- areas the state has designated for industries to locate.
</P>
<P>
   ''This goes like a dagger through those enterprise zones,''
Weichsel said. ''No one wants to have their own drinking supply
infected. But no state in the nation has laws this strict.''
</P>
<P>
   But DEP officials say businesses could work to conform to the
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not trying to chase existing businesses out of these
areas,'' Banach said.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Brown, director of the environmental policies council for
the Connecticut Business &AMP; Industry Association said he expects the
regulations to become more business friendly by the time they're
enacted.
</P>
<P>
   ''Are they exactly where we want them now? No,'' Brown said.
''But they're a lot better than where they were three years ago.
And we're optimistic that revisions will still be made.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The Connecticut Fund for the Environment --
www.cfenv.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
