<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuban Sculptor Rita Longa Dies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA (AP) -- Cuban sculptor Rita Longa, whose bronze and marble
creations grace the capital's Bellas Artes Palace and the Tropicana
nightclub, died Monday of a heart attack, state media reported
Tuesday. She was 87.
</P>
<P>
   Longa began her sculpting career in the 1930s, and won Cuba's
National Salon Award for Painting and Sculpture in 1938. She
received international recognition at the 1951 Gold Medal
Exhibition in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In Cuba, she directed the Center for Monumental and
Environmental Sculpture, and received the National Award for Visual
Arts in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Her death was reported by the Communist Party daily Granma and
the official Prensa Latina news service. A funeral service was to
be held Wednesday in the Cuban capital.
</P>
<P>
   Longa, a widow, is survived by a son and a granddaughter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-30-00 1731 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000530.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmaker: Education Department test results misleading  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- One way the state Education Department
reports students' test results gives a misleading picture of how
youngsters are actually performing, a state legislator is
contending.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Steven Sanders, a Manhattan Democrat who chairs his
chamber's education committee, said the state numbers distort how
many students are taking and passing the all-important state
Regents examinations, the New York Post reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Students for the first time this year are being required to pass
the English Regents test in order to get a high school diploma. In
the future, more Regents exams will have to be passed by graduating
students.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders is objecting to the ''average grade enrollment''
statistic gathered by the Education Department. It records how many
students passed the English Regents, but he said it is misleading
because it does not take into account how many fellow students are
dropping out or failing grades. Nor does the data allow officials
to accurately track students in specific classes as they progress
through the educational system, he argued.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders made his complaints in a letter to state Education
Commissioner Richard Mills, the Post said.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders urged the Education Department to use ''cohort'' data to
track high schoolers' achievement on Regents tests. Under those
statistics, which the department has started to compile, students
are tracked through their high school years to their performances
matched against their peers.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Ray, Education Department spokesman, said the ''cohort''
data will eventually be compiled for students on all five Regents
tests the state will require for high school graduation by 2003. It
is currently being compiled for student performance on the math and
English Regents, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ray defended the value of the ''average grade enrollment'' data,
however. He said when students' passing averages on the Regents
tests are compared with the percentage of students taking the
tests, a clearer picture emerges of how students in various schools
are doing on the Regents test.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
