<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Expands Clean-Air Study  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD CARELLI
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court drew gasps from
environmentalists and praise from industry representatives Tuesday
by expanding its review of a major clean-air dispute. The justices
said they will decide whether anti-pollution regulations must take
the costs of compliance -- not just health effects -- into account.
</P>
<P>
   At stake is air quality nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been a bedrock principle of the Clean Air Act that the
amount of pollution allowed in the air should depend on how it
affects the health of our children and the elderly,'' said Vickie
Patton, a lawyer with the group Environmental Defense. ''A decision
by the court to change the long-standing clean air policy would tip
the scales away from public health concerns and toward the economic
concerns of major polluters.''
</P>
<P>
   Lower court rulings dating back to 1980 interpreted earlier
versions of the Clean Air Act to bar the Environmental Protection
Agency from considering compliance costs when setting
anti-pollution standards. Costs routinely are considered later in
the process, when implementation plans are formed.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Conrad, a lawyer for the U.S Chamber of Commerce, called
Tuesday's action ''terrific news.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The public health is not going unprotected,'' she said. ''The
clean-air standards at issue here are beyond what is needed to
protect the public health.''
</P>
<P>
   Cost-benefit analysis, Conrad said, could force federal
regulators to make principled decisions on air quality, and prevent
adoption of unneeded and unfeasible standards.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's highest court last week agreed to review a ruling
that blocked the EPA from enforcing rules it adopted in 1997 to
reduce smog and soot. The justices had granted a Clinton
administration appeal that said the dispute ''carries profound
implications for the health of the American public.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chamber of Commerce, American Trucking Associations,
National Association of Manufacturers and other industry
representatives who successfully challenged the new standards in a
federal appeals court filed a cross appeal raising the
compliance-costs issue.
</P>
<P>
   The cross appeal attacks those portions of the appeals court
ruling that freed the EPA from taking costs into account and
rejected the industry groups' contention that the air-quality
standards were based on incomplete or poor science.
</P>
<P>
   The industry groups were joined in their challenge to the new
standards by three states -- Michigan, Ohio and West Virginia. Two
states -- Massachusetts and New Jersey -- sided with the EPA in
support of the tougher air-quality standards. The two states, among
others in the Northeast, contend that prevailing winds carry
Midwest pollution to them.
</P>
<P>
   A three-judge panel of the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the
District of Columbia ruled by a 2-1 vote last year that the agency
overstepped its authority. The appeals court panel said the EPA had
interpreted the 1990 Clean Air Act ''so loosely'' that it
unlawfully usurped Congress' legislative power.
</P>
<P>
   The full appeals court voted 6-5 in October against reviewing
the panel's decision.
</P>
<P>
   The revised air standards limited the allowable level of ozone,
an essential part of smog, to 0.08 parts per million, instead of
the 0.12 parts per million under the old requirement. And states
for the first time were required to regulate microscopic
particulates, or soot, from power plants, cars and other sources
down to 2.5 microns, or 28 times smaller than the width of a human
hair.
</P>
<P>
   ''The stakes in this case are very high for the lives and health
of millions of Americans,'' said Howard Fox, a lawyer for the
American Lung Association, which supports the new standards.
</P>
<P>
   ''A difference in standards could mean thousands of deaths and
millions of days in lost work and school absences,'' Fox said. ''We
would be concerned if the court considered opening up the Clean Air
Act to consideration of nonhealth standards.''
</P>
<P>
   The cases granted last week and Tuesday will be argued together
next fall. The court is expected to rule next year.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The appeals court ruling in American Trucking
Associations vs. EPA:
http://pacer.cadc.uscourts.gov/common/opinions/199905/97-1440a.txt
</P>
<P>
   American Lung Association reports on air quality:
http://www.lungusa.org/air/index.html
</P>
<P>
   Chamber of Commerce release on case: http://www.uschamber.com
and click on affiliates to find National Chamber Litigation Center
</P>
<P>
   Environmental Defense statement:
http://www.environmentaldefense.org
</P>
</TEXT>
