<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fallen financier loses another courtroom fight, but spared eviction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- A judge ruled Tuesday that money disgraced
financier Robert E. Brennan made from the sales of his mansions in
Brielle, N.J., and Saratoga Springs, N.Y., must be surrendered to
creditors.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second legal setback for the former penny-stock
tycoon in less than a week.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan, 56, was spared immediate eviction from a condominium in
Juno Beach, Fla., however, when U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Kathyrn C.
Ferguson decided she needed more evidence to determine its fate.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities question the legitimacy of Brennan's sales of the
three properties.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson acted on motions from the court-appointed trustee for
Brennan's now-dissipated empire. The trustee is conducting a global
hunt for Brennan's assets to satisfy the Newark native's creditors.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among the creditors are the Securities and Exchange
Commission and the New Jersey Bureau of Securities, which are
seeking over $120 million for investors they maintain were swindled
by Brennan.
</P>
<P>
   The Brielle and Saratoga homes sold for about $3 million each.
Some of the money has been used for Brennan's legal fees and upkeep
on the Juno Beach condo, including two servants, said Robert K.
Malone, a lawyer for the bankruptcy trustee.
</P>
<P>
   He could not immediately say how much money remained, but SEC
lawyer Judith Starr estimated the amount at several million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan, 56, did not speak in court and declined to speak to a
reporter afterward.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Juno Beach residence, Brennan still has use
of an apartment at Due Process Stables and Golf Course in Colts
Neck, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan relinquished his horse farm-turned private golf club on
Thursday in a deal to gain 60 days to decide whether he can turn
over the assets of foreign financial accounts that Malone has said
are worth more than $25 million.
</P>
<P>
   Malone valued Due Process at more than $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   That deal came as Brennan appeared for a contempt hearing before
U.S. District Judge Richard Owen in Manhattan. It is now set for
Aug. 16.
</P>
<P>
   ''If he doesn't bring (the overseas money) back, we will ask the
court to throw him in the slammer,'' Starr said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Owen ruled in 1995 that Brennan cheated investors and ordered
him to pay what is now more than $78 million to the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan last year settled a lawsuit brought by New Jersey by
agreeing to pay $45 million to investors.
</P>
<P>
   But the SEC and New Jersey authorities say Brennan has
consistently sought to hide his assets overseas, leading to the
contempt action.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC case stems from Brennan's flagship operation, First
Jersey Securities Inc. He appeared in its television commercials in
the 1980s, stepping off a helicopter and urging viewers to ''come
grow with us.''
</P>
<P>
   The SEC charged Brennan employed ''boiler room'' tactics at
First Jersey and manipulated the market in shares of little-known
companies to fleece people called cold by a high-pressure sales
force.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey charged that after closing First Jersey in the late
1980s, Brennan secretly controlled two other brokerages to run
similar scams with low-cost, high-risk stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan denied wrongdoing, but consented to a finding that he
used ''substantial influence'' at the two brokerages to make
''unreasonably excessive profits'' in stocks in which he held an
undisclosed interest from 1988-95.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC has barred Brennan from re-entering the securities
industry.
</P>
<P>
   He also once controlled two race tracks and was chairman of
Seton Hall University's governing Board of Regents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
