<HEADLINE> Palestinian TV, Radio Stations Shut  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Palestinian police raided the offices of a TV
station and a radio station before dawn Tuesday, closing them in an
apparent crackdown on media expression, the stations' director
said.
</P>
<P>
   Police gave no reason for the raid, and director Ammar Musa
Ammar said he did not know what prompted the closures, which in the
past have followed broadcasts that aired criticism of either the
Palestinian Authority or the peace process with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The stations, based in the West Bank town of Ramallah, were shut
down for airing programs that violated Palestinian broadcasting
law, a Ramallah police official said on condition of anonymity. He
would not elaborate, but said a statement would be released later
Tuesday or Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The private al-Nasr TV station and al-Manara radio station have
each been closed three times after airing political messages that
the Palestinian Authority opposed, Ammar said. He said five
policeman raided and closed the stations Tuesday morning without
showing a written order.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian human rights group MIFTAH accused the
Palestinian Authority of showing an ''ongoing disregard for
Palestinian human rights and civil law,'' and suggested the
crackdown was prompted by Israeli pressure to rein in opposition to
the peace process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
