<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two More Die in Zimbabwe Violence  </HEADLINE>
By ANGUS SHAW
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- Two people were killed and scores of
others injured in the continuing political violence raging across
Zimbabwe ahead of parliamentary elections, police and independent
monitors said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Since February, the violence has killed at least 26 people, most
of them opposition supporters attacked by ruling party thugs.
</P>
<P>
   Police on Tuesday reported the death of a ruling party campaign
manager who was shot in a dispute with suspected supporters of
another ruling party official.
</P>
<P>
   Messiah Kufandaedza, who lost a bid to run as a candidate in the
June 24-25 parliamentary election, was shot in the stomach Saturday
near Marondera, 45 miles east of Harare, police spokesman Wayne
Bvudzijena said.
</P>
<P>
   He died Sunday, Bvudzijena said, adding that one suspect was
under arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Police also reported the death Monday of a man attacked by
unidentified assailants in the Honde Valley district near
Zimbabwe's eastern border. Neighbors said the man was forced to
sing ruling party slogans before being beaten.
</P>
<P>
   The political violence began after the government lost a
constitutional referendum in February that would have strengthened
President Robert Mugabe's powers.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign against the proposed constitution was led by an
alliance of opposition and civic groups, who presented Mugabe with
his first serious challenge since he led the country to
independence in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the violence, armed ruling party supporters began
illegally occupying white-owned farms. More than 1,400 farms are
now occupied.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Bennett, a white farmer who fled his occupied eastern
Zimbabwe property two weeks ago after death threats, planned to
return to his farm after police promised to protect him from
violence and stop crimes on his farm, said Topper Whitehead, an
associate of Bennett's.
</P>
<P>
   Police had arrested and were to charge about 10 illegal
squatters for theft of farm equipment and livestock, Whitehead said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Though police in Chimanimani for the first time had vowed to
fight occupiers' crimes, they also said they were too powerless to
force the squatters to leave, Whitehead added.
</P>
<P>
   White farm leaders said Tuesday that ruling party militants
continued to pressure their farm workers to denounce the opposition
and attend ruling party meetings.
</P>
<P>
   In a typical incident last week, two women were beaten and their
babies were thrown to the ground for not attending a rally, said
the Amni trust, an independent group monitoring the violence.
</P>
<P>
   At a campaign rally in Glendale, 50 miles north of Harare,
ruling party officials held a ''roll call'' Sunday of the area's
white farmers and sent militants to farms suspected of not sending
enough managers or workers to the meeting, the Commercial Farmers
Union said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
