<HEADLINE> US Content With N. Korea Nuke Site  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP)-- A second visit by a U.S. technical team to a
suspected nuclear site in North Korea yielded no evidence of
disturbing activities, the State Department said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The team found conditions unchanged since the first visit a
year ago in May 1999,'' spokesman Philip Reeker said. ''It remains
an unfinished site, the underground portion of which is an
extensive empty tunnel complex.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the team reported that the North Koreans cooperated
fully and provided unhampered access for the visit.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea has said, according to Reeker, that the site was
intended for unspecified national security purposes but is willing
to consider other uses for the site, including commercial uses.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that bilateral talks with North Korea last week in
Rome were ''conducted in a serious and constructive manner, and we
made progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeker said the two sides agreed to hold new negotiations on
implementation of a 1994 agreement under which North Korea agreed
to forgo development of nuclear weapons in return for two nuclear
reactors with limited plutonium production capability.
</P>
<P>
   the two sides will meet Wednesday, Reeker said, to lay
groundwork for the next round of missile talks. No date has been
decided for the actual talks.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has been attempting to wean North
Korea from its missile program in exchange for more normal
diplomatic relations and economic benefits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
