<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Civilian Rule Celebrated  </HEADLINE>
By GILBERT DA COSTA
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABUJA, Nigeria (AP) -- Lamenting the continued ethnic and
religious violence in his country, Nigerian President Olusegun
Obasanjo says the ''bloodletting has to stop,'' newspapers reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   His comments came in an address marking the anniversary of the
restoration of civilian rule. Obasanjo was sworn in one year ago to
end 15 years of military rule in Africa's most populous country.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bloodletting has to stop,'' Obasanjo said in the speech
broadcast Monday on national television and published in Tuesday
newspapers. ''We are going to make sure it stops.''
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria is sharply divided along ethnic and religious lines.
Thousands have been killed since Obasanjo took office May 29 last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, fighting between Christians and Muslims killed up to
300 people in the northern city of Kaduna, about 100 miles north of
the capital, Abuja.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting revived the religious bloodletting in Kaduna of
February, when 2,000 died in clashes triggered by plans to
implement Islamic law, or sharia, in some northern Nigerian states.
</P>
<P>
   The government will resist the temptation to resort to the
military tactics of the past to resolve the crisis, Obasanjo said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I shall continue to pursue the course of dialogue without for
a moment abandoning my responsibility to the constitution and my
oath to uphold the laws of the land,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Obasanjo acknowledged that rebuilding the country has only
begun.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria is one of the world's poorest nations despite billions
of dollars in oil wealth. The country's infrastructure barely
functions, and corruption has infected nearly every level of
society.
</P>
<P>
   The government has recovered $1 billion in illegally acquired
cash and assets, Obasanjo said, and $2 billion has been frozen in
overseas bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   In a gesture of reconciliation, Obasanjo said the Ibo soldiers
dismissed 30 years ago for fighting against the government during
the Biafra civil war will be rehabilitated and treated as retired.
</P>
<P>
   Many Ibo people feel as marginalized today as when they seceded
in 1967. More than a million people died in the war, which ended
with Biafra's surrender in 1970.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-30-00 1811 </TRAILER>
