<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death penalty phase begins in trial of shopkeeper's young killer  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOMS RIVER, N.J. (AP) -- Grimly trying to understand why,
relatives and friends of a thrift shop owner who was slain during a
robbery listened in court Tuesday as new details of her last
moments were revealed.
</P>
<P>
   Some wept openly and others grimaced, their heads bowed, as
prosecutors played a tape-recorded confession in which Derek
Lecompte, 20, described how he stabbed Linda Thomas and then
returned to the scene three times in the ensuing hours to find her
still alive.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's hard to believe that someone could be that callous with
life,'' said Douglas Thomas, 37, the victim's husband. ''It's just
beyond me.''
</P>
<P>
   Lecompte, of Toms River, could face the death penalty for the
May 4, 1999, slaying of Thomas, 42, owner of The Garage Depot.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas was stabbed 40 times by Lecompte in a robbery that netted
$375 in cash and some secondhand stereo equipment. The killing was
captured on videotape by a surveillance camera in the store, but it
has never been made public.
</P>
<P>
   Lecompte, who was 19 at the time, turned himself in the day
after the slaying. He pleaded guilty in March to felony murder,
knowing and purposeful murder, robbery and unlawful possession of a
knife.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the penalty phase of his trial began. In it,
Executive Assistant Ocean County Prosecutor John J. Mercun will try
to persuade Superior Court Judge Edward J. Turnbach to sentence
Lecompte to death while his lawyers plead for mercy.
</P>
<P>
   ''His conduct is worthy of death,'' Mercun told the judge
Tuesday at the start of the two-day proceeding. He said Lecompte
entered the store intending to rob it and to kill Thomas so she
couldn't identify him as the thief.
</P>
<P>
   ''I beg you to please accept Derek's remorse for his actions,''
said Helen Szabo, Lecompte's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   She said Lecompte bore the scars of domestic violence: His
mother's boyfriends beat her and him and he was shuffled from
guardian to guardian during his childhood, eventually taking up
residence in a broken-down car while he was still in high school,
Szabo said.
</P>
<P>
   In a tape-recorded confession given to Dover Township police
Detective Guy Murray, Lecompte calmly described how he intended to
push Thomas away from the store's cash register but stabbed her
with a paring knife instead.
</P>
<P>
   ''She screamed out, 'What are you doing? Why are you doing this?
I have a disabled daughter at home,''' Lecompte said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas hit Lecompte with a shelf and tried to kick him before
her stab wounds dropped her to the floor, Lecompte said. But she
was able to get up and come after her attacker again, hitting him
and struggling to get the knife, Lecompte said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the stab wounds -- to the chest, arms, abdomen, back,
neck and ear -- felled her for good and she lay on the floor, saying
''I just want to go home,'' said Lecompte.
</P>
<P>
   He sat ashen-faced, his head bowed, as he listened to his words
echo through the courtroom Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Lecompte said he returned to see if she was alive and each time
found her conscious and talking -- but did nothing to help her. He
found the surveillance system VCR, though, and took the
videocassette tape that was inside.
</P>
<P>
   The tape was found a day later, along with Lecompte's bloodied
clothes, in the Dumpster of an apartment complex.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-30-00 1840 </TRAILER>
