<DOCNO> APW20000530.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Melanoma Treatment Holds Promise  </HEADLINE>
By TODD SPANGLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- A new combination drug therapy for skin cancer
could modestly extend the lives of melanoma patients, a study
found.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers found that the improvement was most marked in
patients with advanced melanoma, especially those in which the
cancer had spread to their livers. Those people are usually not
given long to live.
</P>
<P>
   The two-year study, whose findings are to be presented at a
cancer symposium in Pittsburgh later this week, found higher
survival rates among melanoma patients who combined interleukin-2,
a substance that bolsters immune systems, with histamine
dihydrochloride, which makes certain cancer cells more receptive to
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The study, which was led by the Melanoma Center at the
University of Pittsburgh and involved 56 medical centers, was
sponsored by the makers of Maxamine, Maxim Pharmaceuticals Inc. of
San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John M. Kirkwood, director of the Melanoma Center, said
there is no treatment that has been proven to improve survival
rates for patients in the advanced stages of melanoma.
</P>
<P>
   Malignant melanoma is one of the most rapidly increasing cancers
in the world, with some 90,000 new cases each year. About 15,000
people die from melanoma each year in the United States, Europe and
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Melanoma Center study, an added benefit of the
combination treatment was the ability to give less interleukin,
which is often given in toxic amounts and can result in a sharp
drop in blood pressure, fever, chills and blood leaking into a
patient's tissues.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the lower dosage, most of the 305 patients involved
in the study were able to give themselves the shots at home.
</P>
<P>
   For all the patients in the study, the combination therapy
resulted in a median survival rate of 272 days compared with 245
days for patients who received interleukin alone.
</P>
<P>
   Survival to two years occurred in 25 percent of the patients who
received the combination therapy.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers said published reports have indicated that the
24-month survival for patients treated with higher doses of
interleukin was 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, for 129 patients entering the study with cancer that
spread to their livers, the combination treatment resulted in a
median survival rate of 283 days compared with 154 days for
patients receiving only the one drug.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a forum now in which we need to think about how to
extend the results,'' Kirkwood said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Tom Hensing, a medical oncologist at the University of North
Carolina at Chapel Hill, said it remains to be seen if this or
another treatment may be determined to be the best. But he said the
study is a move in the right direction because it focuses on the
survival of the most serious cases of melanoma and the quality of
patients' care.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is fairly exciting,'' said Hensing. ''I think it was a
well-done study.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   University of Pittsburgh Cancer Institute
http://www.upci.upmc.edu/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-30-00 1851 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
