<DOCNO> APW20000530.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Environmental groups demand sprawl protection in transportation bill </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- With highway funding on a collision course
involving Republican powers at the Statehouse, environmental groups
renewed their pressure Tuesday to have the state's transportation
law address the sprawl they say is choking roads and people.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey Sierra Club Director Jeff Tittel and a host of
officials from other environmental groups said any new
transportation plan must include tough provisions to prohibit
projects shown to aggravate overcrowding or threaten rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   ''New Jersey is a state where if two major highways cross, you
are going to get a mall. You run a highway out to a corn field, you
are going to get an office park,'' Tittel said.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, however, the Senate Transportation Committee
wrapped up a quiet public hearing to fulfill a technical
requirement so Senate President Donald DiFrancesco's $4 billion
transportation plan can come up for a full vote.
</P>
<P>
   There was no agreement at the hearing on inserting any new
environmental provisions and the committee chairman, Sen. Andrew
Ciesla, R-Ocean, said he doubted any changes to the Senate bill
would be made later.
</P>
<P>
   The Transportation Trust Fund is the main system of funding
highway and rail projects, and a funding plan approved in 1995
expires this year. Technically, the fund will run out of money in
June. In reality it has money left over plus an extra $250 million
to work with from a referendum approved by the voters in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   How to pay for the fund after this year has provoked a test of
wills between DiFrancesco, Gov. Christie Whitman and Assembly
Republicans. With the divisions over school construction supposedly
resolved, the Transportation Trust Fund could become the most
divisive fiscal dispute as the state tumbles into June, the
deadline for a new budget.
</P>
<P>
   All agree on how to pay for the fund for the next 12 months with
a diversion from the state's wholesale petroleum and sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   DiFrancesco wants to make this diversion permanent with a
constitutional amendment, and to use the revenue to renew the trust
fund for four years. The amendment was the subject of Tuesday's
Transportation Committee hearing, which Ciesla said should build
support and momentum for it.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman so far has opposed the permanent dedication and does not
want to divert state revenues beyond next year in the event of an
economic downturn, especially with the pending question of how to
finance $10 billion to $15 billion in new schools.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly GOP proposes to split the difference with a
two-year renewal.
</P>
<P>
   In all instances, Whitman's notion two years ago of raising the
retail gasoline tax by 4 cents appears dead.
</P>
<P>
   The demand by environmental groups, however, could add another
speed-bump.
</P>
<P>
   The ranking Democrat at Tuesday's hearing, Sen. Shirley Turner,
R-Mercer, said Democrats in the Senate minority would push to amend
DiFrancesco's bill to include anti-sprawl provisions. Tittel and
William Neil of the New Jersey Audubon Society said they would
press to find Republicans in the majority willing to join them.
</P>
<P>
   Tittel said in the 16 years since the Transportation Trust Fund
system has been in use, state officials have never employed binding
rules requiring an assessment of highway projects with an eye
toward their impact on growth or development. He said New Jersey's
continued congestion and loss of open land in those subsequent 16
years has made it clear this has been among one of the state's
worst mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ''Without any safeguards or assurances at how that money is
going to be spent, we are going to keep repeating the mistakes of
the past, where roads that were designed originally for interstate
commerce became commuter roads, and then those commuter roads
filled up with traffic and we widened them,'' Tittel said. ''You
can't build your way out of traffic jams.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-30-00 1902 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
