<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regulators Eye Changing Media Rules  </HEADLINE>
By KALPANA SRINIVASAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Communications Commission on
Tuesday proposed relaxing some media ownership rules, including a
ban on one entity controlling two networks and a restriction
against one company owning a broadcast station and daily newspaper
in the same market.
</P>
<P>
   A 1996 telecommunications law required the FCC to periodically
review ownership rules in light of greater competition and other
changes in the industry. A report released Tuesday lays out
proposed modifications but will require the commission to
thoroughly examine each item before any changes are voted on.
</P>
<P>
   FCC Chairman William Kennard, noting that the majority of
Americans still get most of their news and public affairs
programming from broadcast stations, said it's important to keep a
range of voices on the airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, satellite TV companies, the Internet and
others sources have provided new competition, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We know that regulatory changes have allowed broadcasters in
large markets to respond to competitive dynamics, without
sacrificing our long-cherished diversity and competition
principles,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC proposed softening rules that ban the common ownership
of two networks so that one of the four major networks -- CBS, ABC,
FOX and NBC -- could merge with one of the so-called emerging
networks -- UPN or WB. The commission would retain a restriction
against any two of the four major networks combining.
</P>
<P>
   Such a modification would be welcome news to Viacom, which just
recently acquired CBS. That deal gave the merged business two
networks, CBS and the fledgling UPN network, which Viacom owns. The
FCC gave the companies one year to shed UPN, but a rule change may
enable them to hold on to the network.
</P>
<P>
   Kennard said there may be powerful arguments to support such a
change, but FCC Commissioner Gloria Tristani, who dissented in part
from the agency's action, warned that a modification would reduce
the outlets available to independent program producers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our first duty is to manage the airwaves in a manner that
promotes the public's interest in competition and diversity,''
Tristani said.
</P>
<P>
   The commission decided against eliminating a rule that prohibits
ownership of a broadcast station and daily newspaper in the same
locale. But the FCC acknowledged that in some cases, depending on
the size of the market, the level of competition and type of paper
and station involved, the rule may not be necessary. The commission
said it would examine what situations would trigger a relaxing of
the restriction.
</P>
<P>
   The Newspaper Association of America, which has petitioned the
agency for years to get rid of the rule, called the FCC's action a
''mixed blessing.''
</P>
<P>
   ''While it has some merit, we think the marketplace and the
diversity of voices that are out there now would easily sustain
full repeal of this outdated rule,'' said the association's
president John Sturm.
</P>
<P>
   An easing of the rule could impact Tribune Co.'s planned
acquisition of Times Mirror, which would give it newspapers in
cities where it already operates television stations.
</P>
<P>
   But the commission decided against making any alterations to a
35 percent limit on the national TV audience one company can reach
through its stations. The networks had lobbied the agency to repeal
the cap, with Fox Television Stations Inc., filing an emergency
petition seeking such relief. On Tuesday, Fox said it would
challenge the legality of the limit in court.
</P>
<P>
   ''The national TV cap . . . long ago outlived its rationale and
is now harming rather than promoting its original public interest
objectives of diversity, localism and competition,'' said Fox
Chairman Chase Carey.
</P>
<P>
   The commission also concluded that it would not alter a rule
barring common ownership of a local cable system and television
station.
</P>
<P>
   FCC officials expect to formally propose the individual rules in
coming months, after which they will be open for public comment
before any final decisions are made.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Federal Communications Commission site:
http://www.fcc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
