<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eritrea Prepares for More War  </HEADLINE>
By CRAIG NELSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   EGALI, Eritrea (AP) -- The tide of battle may have turned against
Eritrea, but its soldiers crouching in caves or under rock ledges
against incoming artillery said Tuesday they're prepared to fight
on.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Ethiopians and Eritreans shelled each other over the
jagged mountains of southern Eritrea, talks began in Algeria to
bring an end to this border war.
</P>
<P>
   The incoming shells crashed against mountain ridges or thudded
harmlessly into the nearby parched plains, sending up plumes of
dust and smoke. Within seconds, the crack of outgoing artillery
resounded through the valleys below the soldiers' redoubt.
</P>
<P>
   Eritrea's soldiers weren't oblivious to the start of peace
talks: They were just making it clear they were prepared to take
back by force what Ethiopian doesn't hand back across the
negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
   Standing atop Mount Egali surveying Senafe eight miles distant,
Col. Habtu Gebrendas, the commander of Eritrea's forces here, said
the choice was Ethiopia's.
</P>
<P>
   ''If they withdraw from out country, good. If they don't, we are
going to take the land back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Eritrea says it has withdrawn its forces from all territory it
seized after the start of the border war in May 1998. Ethiopian
troops, however, have pressed deep into Eritrea beyond the disputed
areas. On Tuesday, Eritrea prepared to push them back if peace
talks fail.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopian forces captured Senafe on Friday. Since then, they
have battled toward Adikeyhe, 15 miles away. Mount Egali -- and
Eritrean forces -- now stand between them and their apparent goal.
</P>
<P>
   For many miles to the north of Adikeyhe, nearly all civilians
have fled with the region becoming a virtual military zone.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-aircraft batteries absent just days ago sprouted from the
rocky landscape around Egali on Tuesday. Tank barrels poked from
camouflaged bunkers. Buses and trucks carrying fresh soldiers,
ammunition and other supplies plied the road.
</P>
<P>
   Four heavy guns arrayed across a valley floor fired thundering
rounds, their barrels flashing with fire and their recoil kicking
up clouds of dust that enveloped the gunners and soldiers loading
the Russian-made shells.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some men and women of Eritrea's army rested in the
crevices of Mount Egali, writing letters, sleeping and cleaning
their equipment. Along a road leading to the mountain, others
stripped to bathe with water they poured from plastic jugs.
</P>
<P>
   Robeil Abraha, a 22-year-old radio operator, said Eritrean
forces killed 1,200 Ethiopian soldiers and wounded 3,000 alone in
just one day of fighting. Only 30 Eritrean soldiers were killed, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Those claims couldn't be independently confirmed, but Abraha
said the Eritrean dead had been buried while the bodies of
Ethiopian soldiers remained on a ridge two miles away where they
fell.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are being eaten by eagles,'' Abraha said matter of
factly.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, fearing the onslaught that soon could engulf
Adekeyhe, some of the few remaining civilians in the town abandoned
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   A man pushing a wheelbarrow packed with all his belongings
paused to catch his breathe under the searing midday sun as he
headed out of town. He wiped his brow with a handkerchief, grabbed
the handles of the wheelbarrow, and trudged on.
</P>
<P>
   A middle-aged woman with a bundle of belongings on her back and
an empty water jug in her hand tried to keep the donkey carrying a
metal chest from straying too far ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the Eritrean capital Asmara, 48-year-old Amanuel Tesfay,
part-owner of a print shop, worried about a war he fears will not
end soon.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm scared,'' he muttered, and turned away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
