<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Jews Help Lebanon Refugees  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Major U.S. Jewish organizations have joined in
an emergency ''Bundles of Hope'' project to rush aid to Christian
refugees who have fled Lebanon for Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The drive to collect toiletries, toys and clothing was initiated
Friday by Malcolm Hoenlein, executive vice chairman of the
Conference of Presidents of Major American Jewish Organizations.
Hoenlein said about 6,500 Christian refugees have left Lebanon for
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the refugees were members of the now-defunct South
Lebanese Army militia who feared retaliation by Hezbollah forces
after Israel withdrew its occupation forces. They are currently
living at a base near the Sea of Galilee and locations in northern
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ''The response has been tremendous,'' said Hoenlein.
</P>
<P>
   He said the response was so great that he halted the appeal for
goods after only one day, though Jewish organizations will continue
to raise cash to help the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Americans were asked to deliver the goods to Jewish federation
offices in their communities.
</P>
<P>
   El Al airlines volunteered to ship all the collected goods to
Israel as soon as possible in any unused freight space, Hoenlein
said. The first of the shipments will be sent Thursday or Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Other organizations participating in the campaign are the
Association of Jewish Family and Children's Agencies, Jewish
Community Center Association, Jewish Council on Public Affairs and
United Jewish Communities (a merger of the former Council of Jewish
Federations, United Israel Appeal and United Jewish Appeal).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
