<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tobacco Accused of Targeting Kids  </HEADLINE>
By MATTHEW PENNINGTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- The chief of the World Health
Organization accused the tobacco industry Tuesday of targeting
children to create a new generation of smokers destined for
premature death.
</P>
<P>
   WHO Director General Dr. Gro Harlem Brundtland warned there
would be a global explosion in tobacco use without international
efforts to ban or limit advertising, raise tobacco taxes and
educate the young.
</P>
<P>
   Between 3.5 million and 4 million people die each year from
tobacco use, Brundtland said. ''This will increase to 10 million in
25 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Brundtland's comments came a day before the launch of World
No-Tobacco Day to highlight what she called a ''lifestyle attack''
by multinational tobacco firms through global advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The companies increasingly target the developing world to get
teen-agers hooked on smoking before they are old enough to know
about the health risks, she said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the WHO, there are around 1.15 billion smokers out
of a world population of more than 6 billion. Growing numbers are
women and children.
</P>
<P>
   Brundtland said the WHO had chosen Thailand for the launch of
No-Tobacco Day because the country had demonstrated the political
will to implement effective anti-smoking legislation, including an
advertising ban since 1992. The number of smokers in Thailand has
dropped around 10 percent over the past 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the WHO launched a campaign for a legally
binding global convention aimed at promoting education,
implementing advertising bans and combatting tobacco smuggling. It
is due for completion by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   David Wilson, regional manager of corporate affairs for
British-American Tobacco, which has a 15 percent share of the
global cigarette market, said Tuesday the industry was being
''locked out'' of negotiations on the planned Framework Convention
on Tobacco Control.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson denied that BAT -- which markets one brand of menthol
cigarettes in 45 countries called ''Kool'' -- was targeting youths
in its marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every day people on this planet do things they choose to do
that aren't terribly wise on reflection, just like driving a
motorbike taxi in Bangkok,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
