<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Outraged Florio denounces rival for hiring private investigator  </HEADLINE>
	   By JOHN P. McALPIN
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- U.S Senate hopeful Jim Florio lashed out at
Democratic rival Jon Corzine on Tuesday for using private
detectives in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Tuesday, Florio called the move
''deplorable and unacceptable'' and said it typifies the arrogance
of Corzine.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's a disgrace to our democracy. He's already made a mockery
of it just with sheer spending,'' Florio said of Corzine.
</P>
<P>
   According to Federal Election Commission reports, Corzine could
spend up to $33 million on his campaign up to the June 6 primary.
</P>
<P>
   Florio claimed operatives hired by Corzine's private attorney
called several of the former governor's staff members asking for
personal information about him, his family and key advisers.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's about dirt. Give me a break. Everybody knows what this is
about,'' Florio said.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine hired New York attorney Stanley S. Arkin earlier this
year after people were photographing his home and calling his
family, said Corzine campaign spokesman Steven Goldstein.
</P>
<P>
   ''He did what seemed natural, which was to call his attorney,''
Goldstein said. ''Jon simply instructed his attorney to get to the
bottom of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Corzine told reporters Tuesday that he was unaware Arkin hired
the private investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ''Jon thinks his attorney overreached, but his attorney had to
protect the interests of the Corzine family,'' Goldstein said.
</P>
<P>
   A visibly angry Florio said hiring a private investigator is
beyond the bounds of the normal opinion research done by political
campaigns. Florio repeatedly denied using similar tactics and said
he never investigated the private lives of opponents or their
families.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not the way we do things in this country. It sounds
like the KGB,'' Florio said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Corzine's use of professional investigators is common on
Wall Street, but has no place in politics.
</P>
<P>
   ''His spending is obscene and what he's spending money on is
despicable,'' Florio said. ''He apparently will say anything, pay
anything and now we find out do anything in order to get elected.''
</P>
<P>
   That makes Corzine unfit for office, Florio said. In the past,
Florio said he would back a Democrat for Senate if he were not the
nominee. On Tuesday, Florio would not say if he would support
Corzine in a November election.
</P>
<P>
   ''I plan on winning,'' Florio said.
</P>
<P>
   Florio admitted his campaign workers went to Christie Whitman's
home to photograph her property in the 1993 gubernatorial election,
Goldstein said.
</P>
<P>
   But those staff members were on a public roadway and they were
there to see if Whitman's property qualified for a Homestead
rebate, Florio said.
</P>
<P>
   Arkin's firm hired a private investigator who had been involved
with the campaign against tobacco company informant Jeffery Wigand,
Florio alleged. Arkin did not immediately return calls for comment
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Florio said he found out about the private investigators three
weeks ago when he was contacted by a former employee. But Florio
waited to address the issue until Tuesday, the day after the
Philadelphia Inquirer reported that Corzine's campaign paid for the
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Rider University professor David Rebovich said the use of
private investigators is not uncommon. Widely available handbooks
tell campaign managers to hire them, he said.
</P>
<P>
   What is unusual is the extent to which the Corzine campaign
appears to have used them, Rebovich said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a matter of proportionality,'' he said. ''It represents
overkill.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
