<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pricey pretzels for GOP in Philly  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Two dollars for a Philadelphia pretzel may
seem like brotherly extortion, not brotherly love.
</P>
<P>
   But it could be worse for hungry delegates to the upcoming
Republican National Convention in Philadelphia. Their Democratic
counterparts will be paying even more for caramelized,
Kahlua-drizzled confections in a city where even the food has
attitude -- Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   In Philadelphia, it's heft that gets people humming.
</P>
<P>
   While the Dems dine on strawberry-peach soup, the Grand Old
Party can plop down $165 for a ''Snacks and Junk'' basket, and dig
into a dozen Tastykakes, a dozen soft pretzels, a bag each of
Oreos, chocolate chip cookies and potato chips, six Hershey's
chocolate bars and six bags of peanut M&AMP;Ms.
</P>
<P>
   You could buy the same snacks, minus the pretzels, at a downtown
grocery store for $47.33. Another 50 cents will get you a pretzel
on a South Philly street corner.
</P>
<P>
   If Republican delegates get really hungry at the convention,
$249 will get them a sandwich in the deal -- a two-foot-long Italian
hoagie, plus a quart each of pasta and potato salads, and another
dozen Tastykakes and dozen pretzels.
</P>
<P>
   Aramark, the Philadelphia-based food giant, won the exclusive
right to cater convention events at the First Union Center. The
company, the world's third-largest food-services company, handles
food sales at other First Union Center events and will also feed
21,000 people at the 2000 Olympics in Sydney this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Convention prices will not differ much from the $5 beers, $2.25
pretzels and $2 cups of coffee that Aramark charges Flyers and
Sixers fans. An Aramark spokesman said the prices -- $25 for a dozen
pretzels, $30 for a gallon of coffee and $25 for 12 pieces of fruit
-- are normal for special events in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are providing a competitive price structure that's within
hospitality-industry and local-market standards,'' spokesman Chris
Hardwick said. ''There are unique and significant costs associated
with this type of event, including transportation, additional labor
and employee training costs, the construction of portable kitchens,
and other costs related to operating in a temporary work
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Aramark will also offer convention groups a ''Society Hill
Feast,'' at $30 per person, that feeds 100 people. The buffet menu
includes chicken marsala, roasted potatoes, chilled poach salmon
with dill sauce, vegetable lasagna, Caesar salad and cannoli.
</P>
<P>
   Aramark will also feed the Democrats gathering in Los Angeles.
Their $35 lunch features a main course of duck-salad on greens.
Dinner is penne pasta with goat cheese, farm-raised venison with
honey and red-wine figs.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone tempted to skirt convention prices with a call to
Domino's should think again. For security reasons, all food
deliveries to the First Union Center will be made at night, when
guards will have more time to inspect the goods.
</P>
<P>
   ''It just isn't practical to call Domino's and tell them to
deliver eight pizzas,'' said veteran convention organizer Mike
Miller, executive director of media operations for the GOP
convention staff. ''You'd never get the food.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one Philadelphia caterer is disappointed that an
exclusive contract was given to Aramark, which contributed to civic
efforts to land the convention and which gives a piece of its First
Union sales to Comcast-Spectacor, which owns the building.
</P>
<P>
   Pam Packard hoped her Manayunk business, Food for Thought
Catering, would secure an $8,000 to $10,000 job feeding members of
the media at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a KO punch,'' Packard said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
