<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: N. America Polution Rises  </HEADLINE>
By TOM COHEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Industrial pollution in North America has
increased for the first time since it's been monitored under the
North American Free Trade Agreement, according to a report released
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The NAFTA-created Commission for Environmental Cooperation found
pollutants increased 1.2 percent in the United States and Canada in
1997 compared to levels in 1995, when the monitoring began. The
pollution totaled 1.4 million tons, it said.
</P>
<P>
   The report monitored the pollution produced by 20,555
facilities, mostly in manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   But the study didn't measure pollution in Mexico, where a
monitoring system is still being set up. And the figures did not
include information on electricity plants and coal mines,
considered major polluters.
</P>
<P>
   Janine Ferretti, executive director of the commission, said the
three countries in NAFTA -- the United States, Canada and Mexico --
want to reduce the amount of air and water pollution.
</P>
<P>
   ''We as a society are not getting where we need to go,'' she
said in a telephone interview. ''There's much more work that needs
to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We, for the first time, are seeing an upward trend'' in the
total pollution, Ferretti said. She said the increase in pollution
transferred by companies for disposal or recycling was particularly
troubling.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Rang, one of the report's authors, noted a large increase
in pollutants released directly into the environment by metals
companies, including steel plants and aluminum refineries.
</P>
<P>
   Companies attribute much of the increase in pollution to
increased production and changing economics, citing lower costs for
onsite disposal compared to transferring offsite for recycling, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a company that used to ship off its waste for
recycling or disposal might now bury it in an onsite landfill. That
method is classified as a direct release into the environment.
</P>
<P>
   The commission has monitored pollution figures for 1994-97, Rang
said. The figures for 1996 were considered intermediate, so the
1997 figures were compared to those of 1995, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   www.cec.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-30-00 2035 </TRAILER>
