<HEADLINE> Fiji Rebel Emerges As Villain  </HEADLINE>
By ROHAN SULLIVAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- A failed Fijian businessman has emerged as the
villain of the idyllic South Pacific, and thus far George Speight's
approach is getting him most of what he wants -- except support.
</P>
<P>
   Speight and his rebel backers are holding Fiji's prime minister
and more than 30 other people hostage in the tiny island nation's
parliamentary compound in a crisis that has gone on nearly two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Speight (pronounced SPATE) insisted Tuesday that the
martial law regime set up a day earlier by Commodore Frank
Bainimarama lacks enough popular support to stay in control, it
remains unclear whether Speight will end up with much power in
Fiji.
</P>
<P>
   Still, nobody has done much to crack down on Speight -- indeed
officials have been quick to negotiate with him -- and such
treatment could bode poorly for Fiji.
</P>
<P>
   Powerful trading partners including the United States, Australia
and New Zealand are not happy about the prospect of a
democratically elected Fijian government being thrown out by a
small band of gunmen -- and they have threatened economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   That could prove painful to Fiji, which depends on timber, sugar
cane and tourism -- but analysts also worry that Speight could
benefit from his political piracy and therefore set a troubling
precedent.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the tragedy of Fiji -- Speights will keep rising,''
said Brij Lal, a history professor and Fiji expert at Australian
National University.
</P>
<P>
   Lal called Speight a ''political son of Rabuka,'' referring to
the leader of Fiji's two bloodless coups in 1987 -- army Col.
Sitiveni Rabuka, who ruled for 12 years after toppling a
democratically elected government.
</P>
<P>
   Speight failed in business in Australia but counted on
connections back home in Fiji to help him get ahead. When his
political clout dried up, Speight struck.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Sam Speight, was a senior member of Fiji's previous
government, which appointed the younger Speight as chairman of Fiji
Pine Ltd. and Fiji Hardwood Corp. Ltd., two companies involved in
managing Fiji's lucrative timber trade.
</P>
<P>
   Speight was fired from both jobs last year after Prime Minister
Mahendra Chaudhry's election.
</P>
<P>
   ''He felt certain he wasn't going to do so well under the new
government,'' Lal said. ''He's a megalomaniac. He's erratic. He's
dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Speight threw Fiji into crisis on May 19 by seizing Chaudhry and
30 other members of the government.
</P>
<P>
   He has sought to mobilize support among the nation's ethnic
Fijians by attacking the ethnic Indian minority that has succeeded
in business and gained greater rights under a 1997 constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Speight is of mixed heritage, with a Fijian mother and a father
who is Fijian of European extraction. But he claims to be
representing ethnic Fijians angered by Chaudhry's ruling coalition,
dominated by the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Among his goals are a new constitution that gives ethnic Fijians
more rights.
</P>
<P>
   Speight hasn't limited his attacks to Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer accused Speight
this week of threatening to kill one hostage, President Ratu Sir
Kamisese Mara's daughter, Adi Koila Mara, an ethnic Fijian
legislator.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours Fiji's military was running the country and Mara
was out as president -- one of Speight's demands.
</P>
<P>
   Mara, who stepped in to run Fiji after the hostages were taken,
had previously indicated Speight and his rebels might be granted
immunity once the crisis ended. The military government indicated
Tuesday it would go along with Mara's promise, according to a BBC
report.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first things Bainimarama did was to throw out Fiji's
1997 constitution -- another of Speight's demands, although it
remained unclear whether the military had acted in deference to
Speight's wishes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
