<HEADLINE> Reform Not on Texas Ballot in Nov.  </HEADLINE>
By CHRIS WILLIAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- The Reform Party, with its roots in the
presidential campaigns of Dallas billionaire Ross Perot, will not
be on the statewide ballot in November.
</P>
<P>
   The party notified the state's elections division Tuesday that
it would not file a petition to place its candidates on the ballot
before the 5 p.m. CDT deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Abt, a member of the party's national committee from
Texas, said the two major parties made it too difficult for his
party, which has never been on the ballot, to get on this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Democrats and the Republicans made the hurdles so high,''
he said, adding that Pat Buchanan, the party's likely presidential
nominee, registered as independent three week ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our likely presidential candidate decided to go the
independent route because he came to the same conclusion,'' Abt
said.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan registered as an independent candidate May 8 by
submitting 129,000 signatures to the Texas elections office, more
than twice the 56,116 signatures required.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Steele, the state Reform Party chairman, has blamed
Buchanan for the party's inability to get the 37,380 signatures
required to get on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Reform Party did not get a penny in assistance from Mr.
Buchanan,'' Steele said during the weekend. ''He would have been a
hero if he would have helped us, in the state that is the
birthplace of the Reform Party, to get on the ballot.''
</P>
<P>
   A call to the Buchanan campaign was not immediately returned
Tuesday. Steele also could not be reached for comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Dees, a spokeswoman for the elections office, said the
Green Party had submitted 74,000 signatures and the National Law
Party had turned in 76,000 signatures. The Constitutional Law Party
submitted 2,200 signatures late Tuesday-- well short of the 37,380
required, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Reform Party is an offshoot of the United We Stand party,
founded by Perot, who ran for president as an independent candidate
in 1992 and 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
