<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000530.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton To Meet With Barak  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton and Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak, meeting Thursday in Berlin, are expected to plan for a
Camp David-style three-way summit with Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   The summit would be in the Washington area, along the lines of
the 1978 summit that President Carter held at the Camp David
presidential retreat to propel Israel and Egypt to their landmark
peace treaty the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Clinton and Barak are likely to discuss at Berlin
earmarking $50 million of Israel's $1.8 billion U.S. military aid
to shore up Israel's border with Lebanon. Israel estimates the
overall cost of a new defense line at $300 million to $400 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli army pulled out of southern Lebanon last week,
erasing a buffer zone that had shielded northern Israel from
cross-border attack.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has provided diplomatic help, mostly
by repeatedly urging restraint by Syria, the dominant power in
Lebanon, and pressing Lebanon to use its army to fill the power
vacuum Israel's withdrawal left.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has not requested U.S. peacekeeping troops for the force
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan plans to augment this summer. The
Clinton administration has not volunteered American soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   From Israel's standpoint, U.S. messages to Syria are vital to
maintaining order along the border.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomatic sources said U.S. and Israeli officials are near
agreement on allowing U.S. military aid to be used for a new border
defense line, thereby sending a message that the United States is
committed to a tranquil frontier.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's abrupt departure prompted skirmishes and rising
tensions along the border and on the West Bank, but the area has
quieted down in the last few days. While the disarray impeded
Israel's negotiations with the Palestinians -- they were suspended --
the current calm is considered a potential spur to positive
results.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has begun conditioning the Israeli public to establishment
of a Palestinian state. He has offered some territory near
Jerusalem to Arafat, who wants to establish his capital in the
city.
</P>
<P>
   However, vital subjects remain undecided including dimensions of
the Palestinian state, Jerusalem's future and whether refugees are
to be compensated.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, Barak and Arafat have set their sights on an overall
settlement by Sept. 13, but February and May deadlines for a
framework settlement passed without results. Israeli and
Palestinian negotiators held preliminary talks Tuesday in Jericho,
on the West Bank, and plan to resume full-scale talks in the region
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Any framework agreement could range in significance from
statements of principle and good intentions to the outline of the
final settlement. In any event, Israel is unlikely to draw a border
on a map between Israel and the new Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   ''Israel is prepared to be positive and constructive in making
this process work,'' Mark Regev, the spokesman for the Israeli
Embassy, said Tuesday. ''But Israel isn't negotiating in a
vacuum.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Our ability to negotiate is also a function of the
Palestinians' coming to the table with a degree of flexibility and
a willingness to compromise,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Barak had planned to meet May 22 with Clinton at the White
House, but the pullout from Lebanon caused him to stay home. The
meeting in Berlin is designed to make up for the postponement. In
the meantime, Clinton sent Sandy Berger, his chief national
security adviser, to Israel for separate meetings with Barak and
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   ''Both the president and the prime minister believe it is
important for them to meet at this time to discuss prospects for
reaching an Israeli-Palestinian framework agreement ... and assess
the situation following Israel's withdrawal from Lebanon,'' White
House spokesman Joe Lockhart said Tuesday in Lisbon, Portugal, the
first stop on a weeklong visit by Clinton to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Barak already had planned to go to Berlin to participate with
leaders of other governments in a ''Third Way'' summit hosted by
the German chancellor, Gerhard Schroeder. It is designed to promote
new approaches to politics that are neither traditionally liberal
nor conservative.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
