<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressGordon Beneke:
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) -- Gordon ''Tex'' Beneke, a singer and sax
player who took over the Glenn Miller Orchestra after the band
leader's death during World War II, died Tuesday of respiratory
arrest. He was 86.
</P>
<P>
   Beneke died at the Assured Horizons rest home in nearby Costa
Mesa, said the facility's owner, Sheryl Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   Beneke joined the orchestra in 1938 and his sunny Southern voice
helped make hits of Miller's ''Chattanooga Choo Choo, ''I Gotta
Girl in Kalamazoo'' and ''Don't Sit Under the Apple Tree.''
</P>
<P>
   When Miller broke up the band in 1942 to join the military,
Beneke played with other bands before joining the Navy during World
War II. Although he played in the Navy Band, he never played in
Miller's Air Force orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Miller was killed in December 1944 after his plane disappeared
and in 1946, Miller's widow asked Beneke to take the Glenn Miller
Orchestra back out on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Post-war audiences went wild for the reconstituted group, which
scored a string of Top 10 records. However, the band's manager and
producer insisted Beneke keep the sounds faithful to Miller's
pre-war work. The frustrated Beneke left and formed his own band.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, he billed the performance as ''Tex Beneke and His
Orchestra: Playing the Music Made Famous by Glenn Miller.''
Rita Longa:
</P>
<P>
   HAVANA (AP) -- Cuban sculptor Rita Longa, whose bronze and marble
creations grace the capital's Bellas Artes Palace and the Tropicana
nightclub, died Monday of a heart attack. She was 87.
</P>
<P>
   Longa began her sculpting career in the 1930s, and won Cuba's
National Salon Award for Painting and Sculpture in 1938. She
received international recognition at the 1951 Gold Medal
Exhibition in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In Cuba, she directed the Center for Monumental and
Environmental Sculpture, and received the National Award for Visual
Arts in 1995.
Stanley Joseph Novak:
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Stanley Joseph Novak, an electrical engineer who
worked in NASA's Apollo space program, died May 23 of heart
failure. He was 61.
</P>
<P>
   Novak developed the backup guidance system that helped the
Apollo 13 spacecraft return safely to earth in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   While at Northrop Corp., Novak adapted his Apollo 13 guidance
system for use on boosters for the Delta series rockets, which were
used to deploy spy satellites for the Department of Defense. His
designs also were used in the missile guidance and stabilization
systems in Rockwell's B-1 bomber.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently Novak worked for GTE Government Systems Corp.'s
Strategic Systems Division in Needham, and worked on highly
classified defense projects, known as the Star Wars initiative.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-30-00 2133 </TRAILER>
