<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coast Guard Details Cuban Clash  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- The Coast Guard released a videotape Tuesday
showing Cuban immigrants swinging a machete and knives and throwing
rocks, cans and bolts from a rubber boat as guardsmen tried to
intercept them.
</P>
<P>
   The 12 were among 51 Cubans repatriated Tuesday. All were among
five groups picked up at sea by the Coast Guard last week.
</P>
<P>
   Coast Guard officials detailed the May 24 confrontation during a
news conference calling for an end to violence by Cubans trying to
reach the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is becoming a frequent and frightening occurrence,'' said
Lt. Cmdr. Ron LaBrec before showing a 24-minute video of the
confrontation 50 miles off Key West.
</P>
<P>
   ''Migrants apparently believe this behavior will increase their
chances of reaching shore. That belief is unfounded and
dangerous,'' said LaBrec, spokesman for the 7th Coast Guard
District in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Guardsmen were given permission to use pepper spray on the
resisting immigrants after being rebuffed for more than four hours.
</P>
<P>
   The men on board the small boat, which was powered by an
automobile engine, were finally stopped and taken aboard the two
cutters.
</P>
<P>
   Several Coast Guard crew members suffered cuts, bruises and
scrapes from the attacks. The Cubans were not injured.
</P>
</TEXT>
