<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia, Eritrea Open Talks  </HEADLINE>
By ANDREW ENGLAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) -- Ethiopia opened talks with Eritrea
on Tuesday, saying it had already won most of its aims through war
and boasting that its 18-day offensive had forced its humbled
neighbor to seek peace.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia announced hours before the talks started in Algiers
that it was withdrawing from one front seized in the latest
flare-up of the Horn of Africa countries' 2-year-old border war.
But a rumble of artillery in the jagged mountains of southern
Eritrea indicated the conflict may not yet be over.
</P>
<P>
   Eritrean soldiers taking shelter behind stony outcroppings
against Ethiopian barrages insisted they would fight until their
neighbor gives back all undisputed Eritrean land taken in the
month's fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no nation that wants war. We cannot accept other
people on our territory,'' Col. Habtu Gebrendas said as his gunners
fired toward the now Ethiopian-held southern Eritrean city of
Senafe.
</P>
<P>
   The southern front in the past weeks has seen the fiercest
fighting of the sporadic war over the countries' poorly delineated
620-mile border. The conflict has cost two of the world's poorest
countries hundreds of millions of dollars and tens of thousand of
lives.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier talks reached a peace accord, but broke down May 6 over
technicalities of implementing it.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia sent its artillery, aircraft and infantry into Eritrea
eight days after the talks failed -- pledging its forces would
withdraw only when they had reclaimed all land seized by Eritrea at
the outset of the war and broken Eritrea's military.
</P>
<P>
   Saying it was at or near that point, Ethiopia declared Tuesday
it had withdrawn from Eritrea's regional capital of Barentu and
other captured territory in the west. The withdrawal could not
immediately be verified independently.
</P>
<P>
   ''As the Ethiopian government has reiterated on numerous
occasions, it has no interest in occupying sovereign Eritrean
territory and, having achieved its goals, it has withdrawn its
troops accordingly,'' Ethiopian government spokeswoman Selome
Taddesse said in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia's capital.
</P>
<P>
   She spoke of a ''humiliating and devastating defeat'' that had
Eritrea begging for new talks.
</P>
<P>
   The indirect talks underway Tuesday in Algeria are sponsored by
the Organization of African Unity with U.S. and European envoys in
attendance. Mediators are serving as go-betweens for delegations
led by the warring countries' foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
   Eritrea already agreed under an increasingly punishing assault
last week to withdraw from all disputed territory and return to the
negotiations without conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Ethiopian warplanes bombed a military airstrip at the
very edge of Eritrea's capital of 500,000 -- taking the offensive to
the central city of Asmara for the first time since the first weeks
of the war. The air raid suggested Ethiopia ''wanted to overrun
Eritrea,'' Eritrean Foreign Minister Haile Woldentensae complained
to reporters in Algiers.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Eritrea appeared keen to show its army remained a
fighting force even as its diplomats sought peace. Officials took
journalists to see the anti-aircraft batteries, tanks, artillery
and troops lined up against any Ethiopian advance through the
southern mountains.
</P>
<P>
   The whoosh of incoming artillery fire and white patches on the
stone peaks around the troops signaled Ethiopian troops still held
Senafe, eight miles to the south.
</P>
<P>
   On May 23, Ethiopian forces advanced 20 miles into Eritrea to
seize the city, emptied by the panicked flight of its 20,000
residents.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to take it back,'' said Habtu, the Eritrean
commander, as the smoke of firing Eritrean artillery engulfed the
gunners, spotters and ammunition carriers.
</P>
<P>
   In Addis Ababa, Selome denied there had been any fighting at
that front for three days, despite what journalists saw and heard
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ragtag cordons of villagers displaced by the southern fighting
trudged toward safety on roads from the front -- joining an
estimated 550,000 people already displaced by the offensive.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 10,000 Eritreans poured over the border into Sudan
Monday and early Tuesday, exhausted and in desperate need of food
and water, the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees said in Geneva.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
