<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Padres Demote Hitting Coach Oglivie  </HEADLINE>
By BERNIE WILSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO (AP) -- After going nine seasons with the same hitting
coach, the San Diego Padres are going on their second one this year
alone.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling that some players weren't responding to his approach,
the Padres demoted Ben Oglivie to their Arizona Rookie League club
in Peoria on Tuesday. He will be replaced on Wednesday by Duane
Espy, manager of the Triple-A Las Vegas Stars.
</P>
<P>
   In other moves, left-hander Sterling Hitchcock, the Padres'
opening day starter, was put on the 15-day disabled list with a
sprained left elbow and left-handed reliever Matt Whisenant was
designated for assignment. Hitchcock, 1-6 with a 4.93 ERA, was hurt
Friday night and might require surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Those moves cleared roster space for the Padres to purchase the
contract of right-hander Adam Eaton from Double-A Mobile and recall
right-hander Rodrigo Lopez from Las Vegas. Eaton was to make his
big league debut Tuesday night against Milwaukee and Lopez is
scheduled to start Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Gwynn, an eight-time NL batting champion and member of the
3,000-hit club, had Tuesday night off due to his degenerative left
knee and served as interim hitting coach.
</P>
<P>
   Oglivie got the job after Merv Rettenmund left for the Atlanta
Braves following last season, his ninth with the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Kevin Towers said it was tough to reassign
Oglivie, and added that some players had told he and manager Bruce
Bochy that they weren't getting what they needed from Oglivie.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's a good person, and I mean that a lot,'' Towers said. ''It
was a little bit of a lack of communication with players. I think
they all really liked the guy a lot as a person, but I just don't
know if they felt they were getting enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Towers said it became clear late in spring training that the
Padres would have to make a change, and they didn't want the
situation to linger the entire season.
</P>
<P>
   ''This wasn't stat driven,'' Towers said. ''You make decisions
on this, it's based on improving not only the players who will be
coming but the current players on your big league club and wanting
them to get better and progress. Even though they're at the big
league level they need to continue to learn and get better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres were with Pittsburgh for sixth in the NL with a .272
team average.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn, who struggled earlier this season because of his knee,
said he got what he needed out of Oglivie.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's really not his fault,'' Gwynn said. ''I just think that
for a lot of the players' taste he wasn't aggressive enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn said he had the same approach with Oglivie as with the
other hitting coaches he's had, and he expects to have the same
approach with Espy.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going to say, 'Duane, when I'm going good, this is what I
do; when I'm going bad, this is what I do. I want you to be my eyes
when I'm up here at the plate and if you see me doing the wrong
things, point it out to me and if I'm doing the right thing, you
don't have to say anything because I'll know.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Nevin, who's batting .328 with a team-high 13 homers and 39
RBIs, was surprised with the move.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, he said he gets as much help from Gwynn and Dave
Magadan as he does from the hitting coach.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know it probably sounds bad, but I honestly don't spend much
time with the hitting coach, except when I was in Anaheim because
of Rod (Carew),'' Nevin said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Even when Merv was here last year, supposedly the best hitting
coach in the game, I relied mostly on Tony and Magadan. Those guys
know my swing as well as anyone just because they've seen my swing
for a long time. It wasn't any different this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevin said Oglivie helped plenty of Padres batters, including
Ruben Rivera, who hit .195 last year but is now batting .262.
</P>
<P>
   Oglivie hit 235 homers in his 16-year major league career. He
had been a minor league coach with Milwaukee and Pittsburgh the
previous 11 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Franklin, the Padres' roving minor league instructor, will
become manager at Las Vegas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
