<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Expos' Irabu Has Torn Knee Cartilage  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI (AP) -- Montreal starter Hideki Irabu had an MRI test
Tuesday that found torn cartilage in his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu, who was scheduled to start Wednesday against the
Cincinnati Reds, instead will return to Montreal to meet with
orthopedic surgeon Dr. Larry Coughlin. Irabu could have
arthroscopic surgery Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu had soreness in the knee after his last start, on May 26,
an 8-2 loss in San Diego. He's 2-4 with a 7.58 ERA in 10 starts,
giving up 72 hits and 41 runs in 48 2-3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Expos got Irabu from the New York Yankees on Dec. 22 as part
of a four-player deal that included right-hander Jake Westbrook.
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Mike Johnson (0-0) will start in Irabu's place
Wednesday. Johnson has made nine relief appearances this season,
but started 14 games for the Expos over the last three seasons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
