<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-30 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fiji Military Tosses Constitution  </HEADLINE>
By ROHAN SULLIVAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- Fiji's new military leaders threw out the
nation's constitution Tuesday and began negotiating with armed
rebels whose seizure of the prime minister and other hostages has
sparked ethnic and political turmoil in this Pacific nation.
</P>
<P>
   As the hostage standoff entered its 12th day Wednesday, rebel
supporters armed with rifles, clubs and knives, vented their anger
by stoning cars, dragging out the drivers and robbing them.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the victims were ethnic Indians, members of the group
that rebel leader George Speight and his followers say should yield
power to ethnic Fijians.
</P>
<P>
   Heavily armed soldiers manning roadblocks throughout the
capital, Suva, did not immediately intervene.
</P>
<P>
   Military officials met Tuesday with the rebels in Suva as the
hostage standoff continued among the lush, tropical gardens and
swaying palm trees of Fiji's nearby parliament complex.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Mahendra Chaudhry and the more than 30 other
hostages -- many of them members of Chaudhry's government -- have
been held captive since May 19 by attempted coup leader Speight.
The rebels want Chaudhry, Fiji's first prime minister from the
ethnic Indian minority, removed from power and Fijians of Indian
ancestry barred from leading the country again.
</P>
<P>
   In his first full day in power, army leader Commodore Frank
Bainimarama revoked Fiji's constitution but said other laws still
apply subject to further decrees by his ''interim military
government.'' Bainimarama -- who took power Monday as President Ratu
Sir Kamisese Mara stepped down amid unrest in Fiji's streets -- told
the BBC he intends to grant Speight amnesty when the crisis ends.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was a promise made by his excellency (Mara) and we intend
to carry that forward,'' Bainimarama told the BBC.
</P>
<P>
   But Speight rejected Bainimarama's authority and said only half
the military supports him.
</P>
<P>
   The rebel leader said he would meet senior army officers for
negotiations to end the crisis but would not talk with Bainimarama.
Speight accused Bainimarama of remaining loyal to Mara, whose
resignation had been one of Speight's main demands.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think Commodore Bainimarama is a lost cause,'' Speight told
a news conference. ''I think he is so blinded by his allegiances to
Ratu Mara that it clouds his ability to take the right decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Later Tuesday, a delegation of four military officers met
Speight's representatives at a theological college near parliament.
Outside the meeting, rebel supporters threw rocks at cars.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Bainimarama announced that Ratu Epeli Nailatikau
had been appointed interim prime minister in the new military
government. Nailatikau is a former army commander and husband of
former President Mara's daughter, Adi Koila Mara, who is among the
hostages inside parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The developments were the latest in a crisis that has sprung
from ethnic tensions in Fiji, which lies 2,250 miles northeast of
Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Fijians of Indian ancestry make up 44 percent of the population
of 813,000, but control much of the commerce. For months, ethnic
tensions have been building between them and indigenous Fijians who
blame the 1997 constitution for giving too much political power to
the ethnic Indian minority.
</P>
<P>
   Speight, a member of the indigenous Fijian majority, had made
the scrapping of the constitution one of his demands. He also wants
his self-styled Taukei civilian government installed. Taukei is a
nationalist ethnic Fijian movement.
</P>
<P>
   A 48-hour curfew imposed in Fiji on Monday was lifted early
Tuesday, and the streets of Suva were generally calm and orderly,
with many people returning to work. But soldiers did not meet
Bainimarama's Monday promise to restrict access to the
parliamentary grounds. Several hundred rebel supporters gathered
inside the complex Tuesday, singing songs and holding traditional
lovos -- a type of barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations and countries including Australia, New
Zealand and the United States have criticized Fijian forces for
failing to crack down on Speight and his allies. Sanctions have
been threatened.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer urged
the military to make way for civilian rule.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want the military as soon as possible -- and I don't mean by
that months later but as soon as possible -- to restore civilian and
democratic government,'' Downer told Australia's Nine Network
television company. He told parliament that Bainimarama has
indicated he will work toward that goal.
</P>
<P>
   When the crisis began, Bainimarama's military took little
action. However, the day after a mob supporting Speight killed a
policeman and knocked Fiji television off the air, Mara agreed to
stand aside as president and the military declared martial law. The
policeman's death was the first in the hostage crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Downer, the Australian foreign minister, said Tuesday that Mara
had been put on a Fijian navy patrol boat sailing off the coast for
his safety.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-30-00 2251 </TRAILER>
