<HEADLINE> Notes From Tuesday's Baseball Games  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressAMERICAN LEAGUE:
Angels-Indians:
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM: 3B Troy Glaus made his 13th error of the season in the
second inning, throwing wildly on a potential double play ball that
allowed the Indians to score two runs. Earlier in the inning, SS
Benji Gil made his 12th when he booted an easy grounder. The 25
errors is one more that the entire Cleveland team. ... With a steal
Tuesday night, the Angels have 38 steals in 52 games. They didn't
get their 38th steal last season until their 103rd game.
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND: Indians LHP Chuck Finley will face the Angels for the
first time on Wednesday. Finley spent 14 seasons with the Angels,
and ranks first in club history in wins, games pitched, innings
pitched and starts. ''It's kind of weird,'' Finley said. ''It will
be strange when guys step into the (batter's) box and I'll have a
story with every one of them.'' ... The Indians sold the rights to
the fans' walkway in left field which is now known as the Pepsi
Home Run Porch. The porch made its debut on Monday when
coincidentally the Indians failed to homer for the first time in 20
games.
Royals-Red Sox:
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY: Kansas City opened a nine game road trip on
Tuesday. In their only other nine-game trip this season, they went
0-9. ... The Royals are 17-7 at home and 8-17 on the road. ...
Tuesday's starter, Jeff Suppan, debuted with the Red Sox in 1995.
He was drafted by Arizona in the 1997 expansion draft and then sold
to the Royals in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON: Trot Nixon, who hit the game-winning home run in
Sunday's epic victory over Roger Clemens and the Yankees, received
a 20-second standing ovation from the crowd before his first inning
at-bat. Nixon hit a two-run homer to give Boston a 2-0 lead. ...
The Red Sox lead the majors with seven shutouts. .... Boston won
the season series 8-2 last season. ... Boston leads the majors with
a 3.47 ERA. They have not led both leagues in ERA since 1914.
Athletics-Yankees:
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND: Jason Giambi began the night 4-for-24 with no RBIs
through the first six games of the Athletics' eight-game road trip.
... With Oakland starting interleague play Friday with a visit from
San Francisco, manager Art Howe is holding off on having his
pitchers work on their hitting. ''When we get home, we might let
the starters take batting practice. We don't want anyone getting
hurt. Kenny Rogers got hurt like that, didn't he?'' Howe said.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: Indianapolis 500 winner Juan Montoya threw out the
first ball. Clearly, he feels more comfortable inside a car than on
the mound -- his pitch sailed wide and wildly over catcher Jorge
Posada and two-hopped off the backstop. ... OF Felix Jose was
activated from the 15-day DL and OF Lance Johnson was designated
for assignment. ... With the Yankees beginning interleague play
Friday with a series at Atlanta, Roger Clemens and the starting
pitchers took batting practice. ... Chuck Knoblauch hit his 28th
career leadoff home run, and first this season, on Tuesday. The
second baseman also turned double plays in the first two innings.
Orioles-Devil Rays:
</P>
<P>
   BALTIMORE: C Charles Johnson and DH Harold Baines returned to
the lineup after sitting out the opener of the four-game series.
Johnson missed two games after being hit in the groin by a foul
tip. ... Manager Mike Hargrove will miss games Saturday and Sunday
at Montreal to attend his son's high school graduation. Bench coach
Jeff Newman will fill in. ... Will Clark, 6-for-26 in his first
eight games since being activated from the DL on May 18, batted
fifth for the second straight game. Baines usually bats in that
spot, but has been struggling (.240, four homers and 13 RBIs) and
shifted to the seventh spot.
</P>
<P>
   TAMPA BAY: DH Greg Vaughn wasn't in the starting lineup for the
fourth straight day because of a strained right hamstring. He
pinch-hit in the eighth inning Monday and struck out. ... RHP Juan
Guzman, on the DL with a sore shoulder, made a rehab start Tuesday
for Class-A St. Petersburg at Lakeland ... Through seven games of a
10-game homestand, Tampa Bay relievers worked 36 2-3 innings
compared to 26 1-3 innings by starting pitchers ... The Devil Rays
have used 38 players this season. Of the current 25-man roster, 11
(44 percent) were not with the team on opening day.
Rangers-Tigers:
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS: The Rangers' 3-2 win Monday marked only the third time
this season that the club won with fewer than five runs. All three
have occurred in the past 11 days. ... RHP John Wetteland's save
Monday gave him 11 for May, breaking the previous one-month club
record of 10 set by Mike Henneman in May 1996 and matched by
Wetteland in August 1998. It also tied the AL record for saves in
May reached four times previously.
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT: LHP C.J. Nitkowski (2-7) has lost his spot in the
rotation. He leads the AL in losses, and his ERA (7.30), hits per
nine innings (13.3) and baserunners per nine innings (17.3) are
second-worst to Minnesota's Sean Bergman. Nitkowski's demotion
leaves the Tigers with no southpaws in their rotation. RHP Willie
Blair will take the fifth spot starting Monday at Pittsburgh.
Twins-Blue Jays:
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA: The Twins have won just one season series (1996)
against Toronto in the past 10 years, going 38-72 in that span. But
Minnesota also won the most important series of all during that
span, beating Toronto 4-1 in the 1991 ALCS. ... Minnesota ace Brad
Radke will start against David Wells on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO: Marty Cordova played against his former team for the
first time since the Twins allowed him to leave as a free agent in
the offseason. Cordova was the AL Rookie of the Year in 1995. He is
Toronto's fourth outfielder and their DH against left-handers. ...
Tony Batista has played in 151 consecutive games. ... Toronto
pitchers took batting practice in preparation for their series
against Florida this weekend.
White Sox-Mariners
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: Manager Jerry Manuel will leave after Tuesday's game
and fly back to Chicago to attend his son Anthony's graduation from
Sandburg High School in Orland Park, Ill., on Wednesday. Bench
coach Joe Nossek will manage the White Sox against Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE: RHP Gil Meche was placed on the 15-day DL with a
strained right shoulder and recalled RHP Kevin Hodges from Triple-A
Tacoma. Meche, 21, came out of Sunday's 14-4 loss by the Mariners
in Tampa Bay last Sunday because of ''a dead arm.'' In 10 starts
and 57 2-3 innings this season, Meche is 1-4 with a 4.21 ERA. Meche
was bothered by tightness in his right shoulder in spring training.
... In 13 games in Tacoma, all relief appearances, Hodges was 0-1
with a 1.77 ERA.
NATIONAL LEAGUE:
Braves-Cubs:
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA: With RHP pitcher Greg McMichael on the DL, the Braves
purchased the contract of RHP Don Wengert from Triple-A Richmond.
Wengert, 30, is 14-29 with a 5.74 ERA in five seasons with Oakland,
San Diego, the Cubs and Kansas City. ''He's a veteran guy, he's
been around awhile,'' Braves manager Bobby Cox said. Wengert will
work out of the bullpen, but Cox said he doesn't have a specific
role. ... McMichael, on the DL with tendinitis in his right biceps,
will be examined Thursday. ... The Braves' two hits Monday were
their fewest in a victory since April 3, 1997, when they got two in
a 3-2 victory at Houston. ... Seven of Andres Galarraga's 13 home
runs have tied the game or given Atlanta the lead in the fifth
inning or later.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: With RHP Ismael Valdes still bothered by a hamstring,
Cubs manager Don Baylor gave RHP Ruben Quevedo the start against
the Braves. ''He tried to do some things to show me he was ready,
but after talking to the doctors yesterday ... I felt the best
thing to do was skip a turn,'' Baylor said. ... Quevedo, called up
from Triple-A Iowa before the game, was on the Cubs' roster earlier
this season, working five times out of the bullpen. He was 0-2 with
a 27.00 ERA in 3 2-3 innings. Since then, however, he has gone 3-0
with a 4.29 ERA in six starts at Triple-A Iowa. He struck out 10 in
his last outing. ... The Cubs have been plagued by a lot of bad
hamstrings this season, and Baylor said one reason might be all the
nutritional supplements players take. The same thing happened when
he was managing in Colorado, Baylor said. ''I saw it with Todd
Helton and Mike Lansing. They had hamstring problems with those
supplements so they had to stop taking them,'' Baylor said. Did he
ever use supplements when he was playing? ''Vitamin E,'' he said.
''A shot in the rear end every now and then.''
Marlins-Pirates:
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA: Manager John Boles said starter Vladimir Nunez's poor
performance against the Pirates on Monday was a matter of command.
''Even if the pitch was a strike, it wasn't where it was supposed
to be,'' Boles said. ... Luis Castillo voluntarily fined himself
after failing to get down a bunt over the weekend in Cincinnati.
Boles didn't want the money but came away impressed with Castillo's
attitude. ''I couldn't believe it,'' Boles said. ''That just shows
you how serious he is about the team and his performance.''
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH: The Pirates will not use fifth starter Jimmy
Anderson on this turn through the rotation because of Thursday's
open date. Anderson has struggled and manager Gene Lamont wants him
to get some sideline work with pitching coach Pete Vuckovich. Also,
Lamont wants to keep his other four starters working on their
normal four days of rest. Anderson's next start will be Tuesday
against Detroit. ... The Pirates have used six leadoff hitters in
the first 49 games. Warren Morris currently occupies that spot but
the job could go back to Jason Kendall, who had it at the start of
the season. Kendall remains the Pirates' best base-stealing threat
and he usually has the team's best on-base percentage.
Astros-Rockies:
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON: There have been 95 home runs in 25 games at Enron Field
this season. In Houston's final season in the Astrodome last year,
there were 118 home runs. ... Scott Elarton, of Lamar, Colo., left
60 tickets for family and hometown friends.
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO: Toby Harrah managed the Rockies while manager Buddy
Bell was in Cincinnati attending his daughter's graduation. ...
Larry Walker took extra batting practice and took his regular turn
in the cage during regular batting practice. ... John Thomson, on
the 60-day DL for a torn labrum injury suffered last season,
returned to Tucson after passing a physical in Denver to begin
light workouts. ... Colorado GM Dan O'Dowd said the Rockies
continue to be concerned about RHP Jaime Navarro, who had been
released by the Milwaukee Brewers and made two starts for Colorado
Springs.
Expos-Reds:
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL: Shortstop Orlando Cabrera was back in the starting
lineup. He missed a weekend series in San Diego due to the death of
his father, Jolbert. ... The Expos were outscored 38-11 in the
first six games on their nine-game trip. ... Tony Armas, the Expos'
starter Tuesday, had never faced any of the Reds' hitters.
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI: Pete Harnisch, on the DL with shoulder weakness,
began playing catch Tuesday. If all goes well, he could begin
throwing off a mound again in 10 to 14 days. ... Reliever Mark
Wohlers had a little stiffness in his forearm Tuesday, a day after
his return to baseball, but it wasn't a concern. Wohlers' pitched
one inning for the Reds' Class-A team on Monday, 11 months after he
tore a ligament in his elbow. He's scheduled to pitch for Dayton
again on Thursday. ... Backup shortstop Juan Castro agreed to a
two-year extension for $400,000 per year. ... The three Reds
regulars who have done the worst with runners in scoring position:
Pokey Reese (.174), Eddie Taubenseee (.182) and Ken Griffey Jr.
(.205).
Mets-Dodgers:
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: The broken left forearm three-time Gold Glove SS Rey
Ordonez sustained in Monday's 4-1 loss to the Dodgers will put an
even greater strain on a Mets' infield that has not played up to
its 1999 standards. The regular quartet of Ordonez, 3B Robin
Ventura, 2B Edgardo Alfonzo and 1B Todd Zeile have combined for 22
errors -- only five fewer than the entire season total of last
year's everyday foursome -- when the departed John Olerud was at
first base. ... Right-hander Rick Reed, who probably will miss
Friday's start at Shea Stadium against Tampa Bay because of a
strained abdominal muscle on his left side, is confident that he
won't need to be placed on the disabled list. ''I'm still a little
sore, but I think after another day's rest that I'll be able to
play catch,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: The Dodgers have until Wednesday to decide what to
do about Carlos Perez. The temperamental right-hander, who reached
the five-year mark in major league service on May 6, had waived his
right of refusal on minor league demotions through the end of May.
The team wants him to extend it another month, but Perez has
refused. The Dodgers' only other options are to release him or
trade him, but GM Kevin Malone said releasing him is not an option,
and no other teams have expressed interest in him because of his
two-year, $15.6 million contract. ... Kevin Elster has approached
manager Davey Johnson and volunteered to play some third base while
Adrian Beltre is sidelined with a strained right hamstring.
''That's been my history -- of moving guys from shortstop to
third,'' quipped Johnson, who received flak as Baltimore's manager
when he changed Cal Ripken's position in 1996 after Ripken played
13 consecutive seasons exclusively at short. ... Mark Grudzielanek,
hit twice on the left elbow in a span of three days by Jason Boyd
and Al Leiter, started Tuesday's game wearing a protective device
on his arm. He is thinking about leaving it on even after he is
healed -- the way Houston's Jeff Bagwell and many others do. ''We'll
see how it feels and how comfortable I get with it, but there's no
question I've got to wear it for a while because I have no
choice,'' said Grudzielanek, who had been plunked a team-high six
times. ''I've taken two blows in an identical spot -- and if I take
another one, I could be out for a while.''
Cardinals-Diamondbacks:
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS: Ray Lankford, who moved past Rogers Hornsby for fifth
in Cardinals career walks with 661, needs two homers to tie Hornsby
(193) for third in franchise history. ... LHP Jesse Orosco, coming
off an injured left elbow, joined Class-A Peoria on Tuesday and
threw 15 pitches at the start of his rehabilitation assignment.
Manager Tony La Russa said Orosco would throw again Wednesday and
then be re-evaluated.
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA: 3B Matt Williams and 1B Erubiel Durazo sat out the game
after having MRIs on their sore wrists. ... The Diamondbacks placed
RHP Todd Stottlemyre on the 15-day DL Tuesday because of tendinitis
in his pitching elbow and recalled rookie reliever Vicente Padilla
from Triple-A Tucson. ... First base coach Dwayne Murphy had
arthroscopic surgery on his right knee and will be out at least
until June 9. Derek Bryant, the minor league outfielders
coordinator, will replace him in the box.
Brewers-Padres:
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE: RHP John Snyder, scheduled to start Wednesday night's
series finale, is 0-1 with a 14.63 ERA and has lost a career-high
seven straight decisions. This will be his third start of the year.
</P>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO: Right-hander Adam Eaton, 22, made his major league
debut on Tuesday against the Brewers. He was the clincher in the
deal that sent Andy Ashby to Philadelphia in exchange for three
pitchers on Nov. 10. The Padres purchased Eaton's contract from
Double-A Mobile, where he was 4-1 with a 2.68 ERA. ... The Padres
also recalled Rodrigo Lopez from Triple-A Las Vegas to start
Wednesday. To make room on the roster for Eaton and Lopez, the
Padres put opening day starter Sterling Hitchcock on the 15-day DL
with a sprained left elbow and designated LHP Matt Whisenant for
assignment.
Phillies-Giants:
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA: An MRI on the sprained left ankle of 3B Scott
Rolen was negative. Rolen, who was placed on the 15-day DL earlier
this week, has a moderate to severe sprain. Rolen hurt his ankle a
week ago in Houston when he turned it while rounding first base.
... The Phillies were 3-4 on their nine-game road trip heading into
Tuesday's contest at San Francisco. They've averaged 4.9 runs per
game during the trip but their pitchers have allowed 47 earned runs
for a 7.17 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO: RHP Joe Nathan, eligible to come off the DL
Wednesday, will make one more rehab start instead with Class-A
Bakersfield. Nathan has been on the DL since May 17 with tendinitis
in his pitching shoulder. ''I'm sure he wants to get back as soon
as possible but we have to look at the big picture,'' San Francisco
manager Dusty Baker said. ''We want him to work on how he feels,
his pitch count, his breaking ball, all that stuff so when he gets
back, he's better than when he left.'' Baker said if he continues
to progress, Nathan would be reinstated in about five days when he
would take his regular turn in the rotation. In the meantime, Mark
Gardner will start Wednesday's game against the Phillies. ... RF
Ellis Burks was held out of the starting lineup because of sore
left leg. Burks was activated from the DL last week after being
sidelined for more than two weeks by a strained left quadriceps
muscle. ''This gives us a chance to rest him and play (Armando)
Rios,'' Baker said.
</P>
