<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Slain Florida Teacher Remembered  </HEADLINE>
By KARIN MEADOWS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- The teacher who was shot to death
in a middle school hallway last week was honored at a memorial
service Tuesday as a beloved mentor, coach and counselor who
reached out to others ''even to the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Students, colleagues, family and friends of Barry Grunow, 35,
carried single carnations and roses as they filed into Good
Shepherd United Methodist Church. Others waited in the center aisle
to view a collage of snapshots of Grunow placed on an easel between
sprays of flowers.
</P>
<P>
   The music of Jethro Tull, one of Grunow's favorite groups,
filled the church.
</P>
<P>
   ''Barry was reaching out with grace, even to the end,'' the Rev.
Bill Corristan said. ''Even to the young man with a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Seventh-grader Nathaniel Brazill is accused of gunning down
Grunow in a hallway Friday at Lake Worth Community Middle School
just before the last bell of the last day of the school year.
</P>
<P>
   The 13-year-old boy, an honor roll student with perfect
attendance, was dismissed early from school that day by an
assistant principal for throwing water balloons.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to school two hours later with a gun allegedly
stolen from his grandfather's house. When Grunow wouldn't let the
boy in his classroom to talk to two girls, Brazill pulled the gun
from his pocket and shot Grunow in the head, police said. A school
security camera captured it all.
</P>
<P>
   A regularly scheduled grand jury was impaneled on Tuesday and
was to begin hear evidence in the case in one to two weeks, State
Attorney's office spokesman Mike Edmondson said. State Attorney
Barry Krischer has said he wants Brazill tried as an adult.
</P>
<P>
   Grunow, who taught English and coached basketball, leaves behind
a wife, Pam, 5-year-old son, Sam, and an infant daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jeb Bush called Grunow's wife, Pam Grunow, on Monday night
to express his sympathy and offer his support.
</P>
<P>
   ''The story of this teacher, this dedicated teacher who was
living in the community, riding a bike to school so his wife could
attend to the needs of their family ... those are real heroes,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   One West Palm Beach radio station, WRMF-FM, devoted its morning
call-in show Tuesday to raising money to help with funeral
expenses. Callers had pledged $10,000 by noon.
</P>
<P>
   At the memorial, the pastor read a eulogy written by Kurt
Grunow, one of Grunow's four siblings. The brother said he was too
emotional to talk.
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate the kind of person his brother was, Kurt Grunow
recalled how when Barry was a little boy he'd go outside and catch
bugs in a jar. He'd then put pennies and nickels in the yard,
because he didn't want to be stealing the bugs.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday evening, an estimated 1,000 people turned out for a
candlelight service in a town park. Hundreds of teachers and
students hugged each other and cried as a bagpiper played ''Going
Home'' and ''Amazing Grace.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd waited quietly as National Education Association
President Bob Chase tried to steady his voice.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's just been too many of these,'' the teachers' union
leader finally managed. ''As educators, we bear the emotional scars
of caring for children in a world where violence is too easy, guns
are too available and adults are too cowardly to take action to
protect our students and our teachers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-30-00 2311 </TRAILER>
