<HEADLINE> Yashin's Arbitration Hearing Ends  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANATA, Ontario (AP) -- The arbitration hearing on whether Ottawa
Senators center Alexei Yashin can become a restricted free agent on
July 1 ended Tuesday night after 10 hours of testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Arbitrator Lawrence Holden has 30 days to make a decision.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a very civil and civilized process,'' said Senators owner
Rod Bryden, who testified for about 1 hour and 20 minutes. ''There
wasn't anybody all upset or anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Yashin, who sat out the final year of his contract with Ottawa
this season, did not testify at the hearing held at the Corel
Centre and was not available for comment afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Bryden said he had a congenial conversation with Yashin.
</P>
<P>
   ''Alexei and I have had a moment when we did not get along
well,'' Bryden said. ''I disagree with him on contracts but other
than that, he's a fine young man.''
</P>
<P>
   The hearing began last week in New York and was expected to wrap
up last Thursday, but Bryden was unable to testify due to a meeting
scheduled for his WorldHeart firm. Both the NHL and the NHL
Players' Association agreed to come to Ottawa for Bryden's
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ''There were no surprises today,'' NHLPA assistant counsel Ian
Pulver said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a typical day in grievance arbitration in the NHL
world,'' he added with a touch of sarcasm.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing started at 11 a.m. and ended about 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL believes Yashin should owe the Senators the final year
of his $3.6 million deal.
</P>
<P>
   A second arbitration hearing is slated for July, maybe in
Toronto, over the league's contention that the Senators should
receive $7 million in damages because Yashin's refusal to report to
Ottawa hurt the club's performance on the ice as well as sales of
tickets and merchandise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
